     <p>
      The
      <b>
       Tesla Model S
      </b>
      is a
      <a href="/wiki/Full-size_car" title="Full-size car">
       full-size
      </a>
      <a href="/wiki/Electric_car" title="Electric car">
       all-electric
      </a>
      five-door,
      <a href="/wiki/Luxury_vehicle" title="Luxury vehicle">
       luxury
      </a>
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Liftback" title="Liftback">
       liftback
      </a>
      , produced by
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Motors" title="Tesla Motors">
       Tesla Motors
      </a>
      , and introduced in June 2012.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-MSlaunch_10-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-MSlaunch-10">
        [10]
       </a>
      </sup>
      It scored a perfect 5.0
      <a href="/wiki/National_Highway_Traffic_Safety_Administration" title="National Highway Traffic Safety Administration">
       NHTSA
      </a>
      <a href="/wiki/Automobile_safety_rating" title="Automobile safety rating">
       automobile safety rating
      </a>
      , as well as being the "third fastest accelerating production car ever produced," and the fastest accelerating car currently in production.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-11">
       <a href="#cite_note-11">
        [11]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The
      <a href="/wiki/United_States_Environmental_Protection_Agency" title="United States Environmental Protection Agency">
       United States Environmental Protection Agency
      </a>
      (
      <a href="/wiki/FTP-75" title="FTP-75">
       EPA
      </a>
      ) official range for the 2012 Model S Performance model equipped with an 85
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Watt-hour" title="Watt-hour">
       kWh
      </a>
      (310
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Megajoule" title="Megajoule">
       MJ
      </a>
      )
      <a href="/wiki/Battery_pack" title="Battery pack">
       battery pack
      </a>
      is 265 miles (426 km), higher than any other electric car at the time.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EPAratings_12-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-EPAratings-12">
        [12]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-13">
       <a href="#cite_note-13">
        [13]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-14">
       <a href="#cite_note-14">
        [14]
       </a>
      </sup>
      EPA rates its energy consumption at 237.5 watt-hours per kilometer (38 kWh/100 mi or 24 kWh/100 km) for a combined
      <a href="/wiki/Fuel_economy_in_automobiles" title="Fuel economy in automobiles">
       fuel economy
      </a>
      of 89
      <a href="/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent" title="Miles per gallon gasoline equivalent">
       miles per gallon gasoline equivalent
      </a>
      (2.64 L/100 km or 107 mpg
      <sub>
       <small>
        -imp
       </small>
      </sub>
      ).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EPAratings_12-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-EPAratings-12">
        [12]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-15">
       <a href="#cite_note-15">
        [15]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The Model S became the first electric car to top the monthly new car sales ranking in any country, twice leading in Norway, in September and again in December 2013;
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SalesNorway092013_16-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-SalesNorway092013-16">
        [16]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NorwayTop1_17-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NorwayTop1-17">
        [17]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NorwayTop2_18-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NorwayTop2-18">
        [18]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NorwayTop3_19-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NorwayTop3-19">
        [19]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and also in Denmark in December 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Denmark2015_20-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Denmark2015-20">
        [20]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Global Model S sales passed the 100,000 unit milestone in December 2015,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelS100K_21-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelS100K-21">
        [21]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and almost 145,500 units have been sold worldwide as of September 2016
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla3Q2016_22-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla3Q2016-22">
        [22]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-VoltUS100K_23-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-VoltUS100K-23">
        [23]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The Model S ranked as the world's best selling
      <a href="/wiki/Plug-in_electric_vehicle" title="Plug-in electric vehicle">
       plug-in electric vehicle
      </a>
      in 2015, up from second best in 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Top2015Global_24-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Top2015Global-24">
        [24]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Top102014_25-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Top102014-25">
        [25]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Model S also ranked as the top selling plug-in electric car in the U.S. in 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Sales2015US_26-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Sales2015US-26">
        [26]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelSTop2015US_27-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelSTop2015US-27">
        [27]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of December 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , the leading markets are the United States with a 60% share of global sales and Norway with 9.4%. Other leading country markets are China, the Netherlands, Canada, Denmark, Germany, and Switzerland.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Top2015Global_24-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Top2015Global-24">
        [24]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of December 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , the Model S ranks as the world's second best selling plug-in car in history after the
      <a href="/wiki/Nissan_Leaf" title="Nissan Leaf">
       Nissan Leaf
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Top2015Global_24-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-Top2015Global-24">
        [24]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The Tesla Model S won awards including the 2013
      <a href="/wiki/World_Car_of_the_Year" title="World Car of the Year">
       World Green Car of the Year
      </a>
      , 2013
      <a href="/wiki/Motor_Trend_Car_of_the_Year" title="Motor Trend Car of the Year">
       Motor Trend Car of the Year
      </a>
      ,
      <i>
       <a href="/wiki/Automobile_(magazine)" title="Automobile (magazine)">
        Automobile
       </a>
      </i>
      magazine's 2013 Car of the Year,
      <i>
       <a href="/wiki/Time_(magazine)" title="Time (magazine)">
        Time Magazine
       </a>
      </i>
      Best 25 Inventions of the Year 2012 award and
      <i>
       <a href="/wiki/Consumer_Reports" title="Consumer Reports">
        Consumer Reports
       </a>
      </i>
      top-scoring car in its road testing. In 2015,
      <i>
       <a href="/wiki/Car_and_Driver" title="Car and Driver">
        Car and Driver
       </a>
      </i>
      named the Model S the Car of the Century.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-28">
       <a href="#cite_note-28">
        [28]
       </a>
      </sup>
      After declining to recommend the Model S in 2015 due to reliability issues, one year later
      <i>
       Consumer Reports
      </i>
      added the car to the magazine's recommended list.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CR2015_29-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-CR2015-29">
        [29]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CR2016_30-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-CR2016-30">
        [30]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In 2016, Tesla updated the design of the Model S, which now looks more like the
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Model_X" title="Tesla Model X">
       Model X
      </a>
      . The 60, 60D, 70, 70D, 75, 75D and 90D versions are available. 70 and 70D Model S owners have the option to unlock the 75 kWh capacity via a software update, adding up to 19 miles (31 km) per charge.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-31">
       <a href="#cite_note-31">
        [31]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The 60 and 60D, reintroduced in June 2016, owners have a
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$9,000
      </span>
      anytime option to unlock the full 75 kWh capacity via a software update.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-32">
       <a href="#cite_note-32">
        [32]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In August 2016, Tesla introduced the P100D to be the new top-level model. The P100D model has a 100kWh battery, a 0–60 mph (0–97 km/h) time of 2.5 seconds and over 300 miles (485 km) of EPA rated range.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-P100D_33-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-P100D-33">
        [33]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
     </p>

     <p>
     </p>
     <h2>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="History">
       History
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h2>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_(108).JPG">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1920" data-file-width="2560" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Tesla_Model_S_%28108%29.JPG/220px-Tesla_Model_S_%28108%29.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Tesla_Model_S_%28108%29.JPG/330px-Tesla_Model_S_%28108%29.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Tesla_Model_S_%28108%29.JPG/440px-Tesla_Model_S_%28108%29.JPG 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_(108).JPG" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Tesla Model S prototype at the 2009
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Frankfurt_Motor_Show" title="Frankfurt Motor Show">
         Frankfurt Motor Show
        </a>
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      The Model S was styled by
      <a href="/wiki/Franz_von_Holzhausen" title="Franz von Holzhausen">
       Franz von Holzhausen
      </a>
      , who previously worked for
      <a href="/wiki/Mazda_North_American_Operations" title="Mazda North American Operations">
       Mazda North American Operations
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Wert_34-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Wert-34">
        [34]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The car was codenamed
      <i>
       WhiteStar
      </i>
      during research and preliminary development.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Brian_Lam_1-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Brian_Lam-1">
        [1]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Merritt_Johnson_2-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Merritt_Johnson-2">
        [2]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Samuel_Abuelsamid_3-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Samuel_Abuelsamid-3">
        [3]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The Model S was announced in a press release on June 30, 2008.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-35">
       <a href="#cite_note-35">
        [35]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-randt_36-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-randt-36">
        [36]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The prototype vehicle was displayed at a press conference on March 26, 2009.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-prototype_37-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-prototype-37">
        [37]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In February 2008 it was reported that Tesla Motors was planning to offer a
      <a href="/wiki/Range_extender_(vehicle)" title="Range extender (vehicle)">
       range-extended
      </a>
      version of its Model S. This version would have included a
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Gasoline_engine" title="Gasoline engine">
       gasoline engine
      </a>
      to extend the driving range of the vehicle,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-38">
       <a href="#cite_note-38">
        [38]
       </a>
      </sup>
      but it was removed in later revisions. At the GoingGreen conference in September 2008 Tesla's CEO,
      <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk" title="Elon Musk">
       Elon Musk
      </a>
      , announced that Tesla was developing only electric cars.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-39">
       <a href="#cite_note-39">
        [39]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Construction of an assembly factory in
      <a href="/wiki/Albuquerque,_New_Mexico" title="Albuquerque, New Mexico">
       Albuquerque, New Mexico
      </a>
      (a central location for shipping) was supposed to begin in April 2007, but was cancelled.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-40">
       <a href="#cite_note-40">
        [40]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A factory to be built in
      <a href="/wiki/San_Jose,_California" title="San Jose, California">
       San Jose, California
      </a>
      was also announced.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-41">
       <a href="#cite_note-41">
        [41]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-42">
       <a href="#cite_note-42">
        [42]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-43">
       <a href="#cite_note-43">
        [43]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In May 2010 Tesla announced it would produce the Model S at the former
      <a href="/wiki/NUMMI" title="NUMMI">
       NUMMI
      </a>
      assembly plant in Fremont, California,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-44">
       <a href="#cite_note-44">
        [44]
       </a>
      </sup>
      now known as the
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Factory" title="Tesla Factory">
       Tesla Factory
      </a>
      . This third plan was implemented.
     </p>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:First_Tesla_Model_S_3rd_anniversary_2015.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="3488" data-file-width="5395" height="142" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/First_Tesla_Model_S_3rd_anniversary_2015.jpg/220px-First_Tesla_Model_S_3rd_anniversary_2015.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/First_Tesla_Model_S_3rd_anniversary_2015.jpg/330px-First_Tesla_Model_S_3rd_anniversary_2015.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/First_Tesla_Model_S_3rd_anniversary_2015.jpg/440px-First_Tesla_Model_S_3rd_anniversary_2015.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:First_Tesla_Model_S_3rd_anniversary_2015.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        The first production Tesla Model S (with owner Tesla Board member
        <a href="/wiki/Steve_Jurvetson" title="Steve Jurvetson">
         Steve Jurvetson
        </a>
        ) in June 2015, three years after the car's market release
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      In June 2015, three years after the Model S introduction and with almost 75,000 Model S sedans delivered worldwide, Tesla announced that Model S owners have accumulated over 1 billion electric miles (1.6 billion km) traveled, and saved more than half a million tons of
      <a href="/wiki/Carbon_dioxide" title="Carbon dioxide">
       CO
       <sub>
        2
       </sub>
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-45">
       <a href="#cite_note-45">
        [45]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1BiMiles_46-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-1BiMiles-46">
        [46]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Tesla Model S is the first plug-in electric vehicle to reach that milestone. In October 2014 General Motors reported that Volt owners had accumulated a total of 629 million all-electric miles (over 1 billion kilometers) out of a total of 1 billion miles (1.6 billion km) traveled; while Nissan reported in December 2014 that Leaf owners had traveled 625 million miles (1 billion kilometers).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1BiMiles_46-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-1BiMiles-46">
        [46]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla also reported that 68% of Model S travel took place in North America, 25% in Europe and 7% in Asia-Pacific.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1BiMiles_46-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-1BiMiles-46">
        [46]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Global Model S sales passed the 100,000 unit milestone in December 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelS100K_21-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelS100K-21">
        [21]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In 2016, a racing series called the "Electric GT World Series" was promoted in preparation for a 2017 racing season using the P85+ as a race car on certain traditional tracks. The first season is planned to have 20 cars in 10 teams.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-47">
       <a href="#cite_note-47">
        [47]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In April 2016, a refresh Model S was introduced. The front fascia has with a similar design as the
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Model_X" title="Tesla Model X">
       Model X
      </a>
      , and also adaptive LED headlights were introduced. Also, the improved Model S has a
      <a href="/wiki/HEPA" title="HEPA">
       HEPA
      </a>
      air filtration system that removes at least 99.97% of particulate exhaust pollution and all allergens, bacteria, and other contaminants from cabin air. The standard charger was upgraded from 40 to 48 amps in order to enable faster charging when connected to higher-amp outlets. Two new interior choices were added: figured ash wood and dark ash wood. These improvements were accompanied by a
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$1,500
      </span>
      price increase in the base model.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-48">
       <a href="#cite_note-48">
        [48]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h2>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Production">
       Production
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Production">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h2>
     <div class="hatnote" role="note">
      Main article:
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Factory#Tesla_Model_S_manufacturing_process" title="Tesla Factory">
       Tesla Factory § Tesla Model S manufacturing process
      </a>
     </div>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_auto_bots.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="3564" data-file-width="5100" height="154" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Tesla_auto_bots.jpg/220px-Tesla_auto_bots.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Tesla_auto_bots.jpg/330px-Tesla_auto_bots.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Tesla_auto_bots.jpg/440px-Tesla_auto_bots.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_auto_bots.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        A Tesla Model S being manufactured at the
        <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Factory" title="Tesla Factory">
         Tesla Factory
        </a>
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      Tesla manufactures the Model S at the 5.4 million square foot
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-49">
       <a href="#cite_note-49">
        [49]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Factory" title="Tesla Factory">
       Tesla Factory
      </a>
      in
      <a href="/wiki/Fremont,_California" title="Fremont, California">
       Fremont, California
      </a>
      . For the European market, Tesla assembles and distributes from its European Distribution Center in
      <a href="/wiki/Tilburg" title="Tilburg">
       Tilburg
      </a>
      , the Netherlands.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-50">
       <a href="#cite_note-50">
        [50]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Cars are built and tested in Fremont, California. The battery pack, the electric motor and parts are disassembled and shipped separately to Tilburg, where the cars are reassembled.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tilburg_51-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tilburg-51">
        [51]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The center occupies a 203,000 sq ft (18,900 m
      <sup>
       2
      </sup>
      ) industrial building that also serves as a workshop and spare parts warehouse. Tesla expects the Model S to "pay back" the energy that went into producing the car in fewer than 10,000 miles (16,000 km).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-52">
       <a href="#cite_note-52">
        [52]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The first ten customers received their cars at the Fremont factory on June 22, 2012 at the official launch.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-InsideTesla_53-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-InsideTesla-53">
        [53]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Production grew from 15–20 cars completed/week in August 2012
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-InsideTesla_53-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-InsideTesla-53">
        [53]
       </a>
      </sup>
      to about 1,000 cars per week in 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-te2015-05-02_54-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-te2015-05-02-54">
        [54]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In October 2015, Tesla Motors announced the company is negotiating with the Chinese government on producing its electric cars domestically. Local production has the potential to reduce the sales prices of Tesla models by a third.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-China092015_55-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-China092015-55">
        [55]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A Model S starts at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$71,500
      </span>
      in the U.S., while in China pricing starts at CN¥673,000, about
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$106,000
      </span>
      , after duties and other taxes.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-56">
       <a href="#cite_note-56">
        [56]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk" title="Elon Musk">
       Elon Musk
      </a>
      clarified that production will remain in the U.S., but if there's sufficient local demand for the
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Model_3" title="Tesla Model 3">
       Tesla Model 3
      </a>
      in China, a factory could be built in the country as soon as a year after the launch of the new model. Production in Europe will also depend on the region's demand for the Model 3.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-57">
       <a href="#cite_note-57">
        [57]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h2>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Design">
       Design
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Design">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h2>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Motors_Model_S_base.JPG">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1431" data-file-width="2153" height="146" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Tesla_Motors_Model_S_base.JPG/220px-Tesla_Motors_Model_S_base.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Tesla_Motors_Model_S_base.JPG/330px-Tesla_Motors_Model_S_base.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Tesla_Motors_Model_S_base.JPG/440px-Tesla_Motors_Model_S_base.JPG 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Motors_Model_S_base.JPG" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Model S chassis, on display at
        <a href="/wiki/Santana_Row" title="Santana Row">
         Santana Row
        </a>
        in
        <a href="/wiki/San_Jose,_California" title="San Jose, California">
         San Jose, California
        </a>
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      The Model S exists in several versions, differing in energy capacity (battery size), power (motor size), and equipment. It is
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Car_classifications" title="Car classifications">
       classified
      </a>
      as a fullsize luxury car in the USA, or as a "Large Car"
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-58">
       <a href="#cite_note-58">
        [58]
       </a>
      </sup>
      (120 cu ft or more) or "Luxury Sedan"
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-59">
       <a href="#cite_note-59">
        [59]
       </a>
      </sup>
      by the EPA. The
      <a href="/wiki/Euro_Car_Segment" title="Euro Car Segment">
       Euro Car Segment
      </a>
      classification is
      <a href="/wiki/S-segment" title="S-segment">
       S-segment
      </a>
      (sports car),
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-60">
       <a href="#cite_note-60">
        [60]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-61">
       <a href="#cite_note-61">
        [61]
       </a>
      </sup>
      or "Oberklasse" in Germany.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SalesGer2015_62-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-SalesGer2015-62">
        [62]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Powertrain">
       Powertrain
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Powertrain">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_motor_cutout.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2448" data-file-width="3264" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Tesla_Model_S_motor_cutout.jpg/220px-Tesla_Model_S_motor_cutout.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Tesla_Model_S_motor_cutout.jpg/330px-Tesla_Model_S_motor_cutout.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Tesla_Model_S_motor_cutout.jpg/440px-Tesla_Model_S_motor_cutout.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_motor_cutout.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Cutaway view of a Tesla Model S drive motor
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B_60_kW_Regenerative_Braking_(cropped).jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="311" data-file-width="357" height="192" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B_60_kW_Regenerative_Braking_%28cropped%29.jpg/220px-Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B_60_kW_Regenerative_Braking_%28cropped%29.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B_60_kW_Regenerative_Braking_%28cropped%29.jpg/330px-Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B_60_kW_Regenerative_Braking_%28cropped%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5c/Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B_60_kW_Regenerative_Braking_%28cropped%29.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B_60_kW_Regenerative_Braking_(cropped).jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        A Tesla Model S P85+ using
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Regenerative_braking" title="Regenerative braking">
         regenerative braking
        </a>
        power in excess of 60 kW. During regenerative braking the power indicator is green.
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      The 2012 Tesla Model S Performance model has a
      <a href="/wiki/Three-phase_electric_power" title="Three-phase electric power">
       three phase
      </a>
      , four pole
      <a href="/wiki/Alternating_current" title="Alternating current">
       AC
      </a>
      <a href="/wiki/Induction_motor" title="Induction motor">
       induction
      </a>
      416 hp (310 kW) and 443 ft·lb (600 N·m) rear-mounted electric motor with copper
      <a href="/wiki/Rotor_(electric)" title="Rotor (electric)">
       rotor
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-model_s_specs_63-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-model_s_specs-63">
        [63]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The base model uses a 362 hp (270 kW) and 325 ft·lb (440 N·m) motor. The company claimed a
      <a href="/wiki/Drag_coefficient" title="Drag coefficient">
       drag coefficient
      </a>
      of
      <a href="/wiki/Automobile_drag_coefficient" title="Automobile drag coefficient">
       <i>
        C
       </i>
       <small style="position:relative;top:4px;;right:1px;">
        <i>
         d
        </i>
       </small>
      </a>
      =0.24,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-DC_64-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-DC-64">
        [64]
       </a>
      </sup>
      lower than any car when released.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-65">
       <a href="#cite_note-65">
        [65]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Independent measurement by
      <i>
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Car_And_Driver" title="Car And Driver">
        Car And Driver
       </a>
      </i>
      in May 2014 bore out Tesla's claim by exactly confirming a drag coefficient of
      <i>
       C
      </i>
      <small style="position:relative;top:4px;;right:1px;">
       <i>
        d
       </i>
      </small>
      =0.24.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-66">
       <a href="#cite_note-66">
        [66]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The rear axle has a traditional
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Open_differential" title="Open differential">
       open differential
      </a>
      . Models with dual motors also have an open differential on the front axles as well. The front and rear axles have no mechanical linkage – with dual motors the power distribution among them is controlled
      <a href="/wiki/Electronic_differential" title="Electronic differential">
       electronically
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-67">
       <a href="#cite_note-67">
        [67]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The Model S P90D has a top speed of 155 mph (249 km/h) and it accelerates from 0 to 60 miles per hour (0 to 97 km/h) in
      <span class="nowrap">
       2.8 seconds
      </span>
      , despite the lower total motor power, in part due to the improved traction of the all-wheel drive powertrain. The Model S P85D, a dual motor all-wheel drive vehicle has a
      <a href="/wiki/Speed_limiter#Fixed" title="Speed limiter">
       governed top speed
      </a>
      of 155 mph (249 km/h)
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cdsP85Dlong_68-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-cdsP85Dlong-68">
        [68]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and it accelerates from 0 to 60 miles per hour (0 to 97 km/h) in
      <span class="nowrap">
       3.2 seconds
      </span>
      (tested to
      <span class="nowrap">
       3.1 seconds
      </span>
      ), under "Insane Mode", with 1
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Gee_force" title="Gee force">
       g
      </a>
      of acceleration.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cdsP85Dlong_68-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-cdsP85Dlong-68">
        [68]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-69">
       <a href="#cite_note-69">
        [69]
       </a>
      </sup>
      New P85Ds have an optional "Ludicrous Mode" hardware package available with the 90 kWh battery upgrade (thus becoming a P90D) that improves the 0 to 60 miles per hour (0 to 97 km/h) acceleration to
      <span class="nowrap">
       2.8 seconds
      </span>
      and 1.1g.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TMspecsBat_70-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-TMspecsBat-70">
        [70]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-71">
       <a href="#cite_note-71">
        [71]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-72">
       <a href="#cite_note-72">
        [72]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla initially reported the total output in the P85D as the arithmetic addition of the maximum power of the individual electric motors at 691 hp (515 kW) but later reported it as 463 hp (345 kW) because the two motors do not give their maximum power at the same time.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-73">
       <a href="#cite_note-73">
        [73]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The powertrain also provides regenerative braking power of more than 60 kW which reduces both energy consumption and improves brake lifetime.
     </p>
     <p>
      Owners reported many powertrain issues from 2012, improving significantly over the years.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-eltk-degrade_74-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-eltk-degrade-74">
        [74]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In July 2015, Tesla announced its goal to make the Model S powertrain last for one million miles.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-autoblog20150715_75-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-autoblog20150715-75">
        [75]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Dual-motor_all-wheel-drive_versions">
       Dual-motor all-wheel-drive versions
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Dual-motor all-wheel-drive versions">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      On October 9, 2014, Tesla announced the introduction of All Wheel Drive (AWD) versions of the Model S's 60, 85, and P85 models, designated by a
      <i>
       D
      </i>
      at the end of the model number.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-BO_76-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-BO-76">
        [76]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-:0_77-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-:0-77">
        [77]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-IND_78-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-IND-78">
        [78]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      On April 8, 2015, Tesla introduced the Model S 70D as its new
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$75,000
      </span>
      entry-level car, with all-wheel drive and an improved range of 240 miles (385 km). The 70D replaced the 60 and 60D in the Model S lineup, with the latter two models no longer being available for purchase. The P85 option was also dropped.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-David_Noland_79-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-David_Noland-79">
        [79]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-80">
       <a href="#cite_note-80">
        [80]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In the 85D, the rear drive unit is replaced by a smaller one to save cost and weight, while a second motor of similar size is added to the front wheels. This results in an
      <a href="/wiki/Four-wheel_drive" title="Four-wheel drive">
       AWD
      </a>
      car with comparable power and acceleration to the RWD version while keeping the price increase to
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$5,000
      </span>
      . Additionally, the 85D reports a 2% (5-mile) range increase and 11% increase in top speed over the 85
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-my.teslamotors.com_81-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-my.teslamotors.com-81">
        [81]
       </a>
      </sup>
      (presumably due to incremental improvements in hardware and software). In the P85D, the high-power rear drive unit is retained, while a new front drive motor boosts the total power by about 50%. This results in a significant increase in acceleration and top speed. The 85 kWh version rose from
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$81,070
      </span>
      to
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$86,070
      </span>
      , while the P85 (now the P85D) jumped from
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$94,570
      </span>
      to
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$105,670
      </span>
      . Deliveries of the P85D started in December 2014, with the 85D models starting in February 2015, and the 70D models starting in April 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-:0_77-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-:0-77">
        [77]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      On June 9, 2016, Tesla reintroduced the 60 and 60D, which has a 75 kWh battery, locked out to 60 kWh
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-82">
       <a href="#cite_note-82">
        [82]
       </a>
      </sup>
      but upgradable by software, as is the Autopilot option. The spring refresh of 2016 also offers the "Bioweapon Defense Mode" airfilter first offered on the Model X.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-83">
       <a href="#cite_note-83">
        [83]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      On August 23, 2016, Tesla introduced the Model S P100D with Ludicrous Mode as its new
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$134,500
      </span>
      top-level car, with all-wheel drive and an improved EPA estimated range of 315 miles (505 km).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-P100D_33-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-P100D-33">
        [33]
       </a>
      </sup>
      This version of the Model S is notable for being the first electric vehicle to have a U.S. EPA estimated range greater than 300 miles (485 km) and for being the fastest accelerating vehicle currently in production, with a 0–60 mph (0–97 km/h) time of 2.5 seconds, when optioned with Ludicrous Mode.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-auto1_84-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-auto1-84">
        [84]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-85">
       <a href="#cite_note-85">
        [85]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Battery">
       Battery
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Battery">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <table class="infobox" style="width:22em;float: right; clear: right; margin:0 0 1.0em 1.0em">
      <caption>
       External images
      </caption>
      <tr>
       <td colspan="2" style="text-align:center;text-align: left">
        <img alt="" data-file-height="512" data-file-width="512" height="16" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/16px-Searchtool.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/24px-Searchtool.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/32px-Searchtool.svg.png 2x" width="16"/>
        <a class="external text" href="https://www.teslamotors.com/sites/default/files/blog_images/driving-range-for-the-model-s-family-chart1.png" rel="nofollow">
         Speed-dependent ranges of various Model S
        </a>
       </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
       <td colspan="2" style="text-align:center;text-align: left">
        <img alt="" data-file-height="512" data-file-width="512" height="16" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/16px-Searchtool.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/24px-Searchtool.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/32px-Searchtool.svg.png 2x" width="16"/>
        <a class="external text" href="https://www.teslamotors.com/sites/default/files/graph1.jpg" rel="nofollow">
         Speed-dependent ranges, Roadster &amp; Model S
        </a>
       </td>
      </tr>
     </table>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Lithium-Ion_Cell_cylindric.JPG">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2532" data-file-width="2737" height="204" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6b/Lithium-Ion_Cell_cylindric.JPG/220px-Lithium-Ion_Cell_cylindric.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6b/Lithium-Ion_Cell_cylindric.JPG/330px-Lithium-Ion_Cell_cylindric.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6b/Lithium-Ion_Cell_cylindric.JPG/440px-Lithium-Ion_Cell_cylindric.JPG 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Lithium-Ion_Cell_cylindric.JPG" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Cylindrical cell (18650) prior to assembly. Several thousand of them form the Tesla Model S battery (see
        <a href="/wiki/Gigafactory_1#Background" title="Gigafactory 1">
         Gigafactory
        </a>
        ).
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      In 2012, the EPA
      <a href="/wiki/All-electric_range" title="All-electric range">
       range
      </a>
      for the 60 kWh battery pack model was 208 mi (335 km)
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Range60kWh_86-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Range60kWh-86">
        [86]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and the 85 kWh battery was 265 miles (426 km).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EPAratings_12-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-EPAratings-12">
        [12]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-87">
       <a href="#cite_note-87">
        [87]
       </a>
      </sup>
      According to Musk, the Model S has a battery with twice the energy density of that on the Nissan Leaf, but the difference in range is more than double. This is also due to other factors such as drag coefficient, weight, engine efficiency and rolling resistance.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-88">
       <a href="#cite_note-88">
        [88]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Musk stated that driving at 65 mph (105 km/h), under normal conditions, gives a reasonable range of 250 miles (400 km).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-89">
       <a href="#cite_note-89">
        [89]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The energy-saving sleep state powers off the display and other vehicle electronics, after the car goes to sleep. This increases the time it takes the touchscreen and instrument panel to become usable. This mode can decrease the loss of the car's range when not being used (2.3 mi, 3.7 km per day, as of 2013
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      ).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-vampire_90-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-vampire-90">
        [90]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The 85 kWh battery pack weighs 1,200 lb (540 kg)
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-rope_91-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-rope-91">
        [91]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="noprint Inline-Template noprint Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">
       [
       <i>
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTRS" title="Wikipedia:NOTRS">
         <span title="WP:CIRCULAR (April 2016)">
          better source needed
         </span>
        </a>
       </i>
       ]
      </sup>
      and contains 7,104
      <a href="/wiki/Lithium-ion_battery" title="Lithium-ion battery">
       lithium-ion battery
      </a>
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/18650" title="18650">
       cells
      </a>
      in 16 modules
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-92">
       <a href="#cite_note-92">
        [92]
       </a>
      </sup>
      wired in series (14 in the flat section and two stacked on the front).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-93">
       <a href="#cite_note-93">
        [93]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Each module contains 6 groups
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-94">
       <a href="#cite_note-94">
        [94]
       </a>
      </sup>
      of 74 cells
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ReferenceA_95-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ReferenceA-95">
        [95]
       </a>
      </sup>
      wired in parallel; the 6 groups are then wired in series within the module.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ReferenceA_95-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-ReferenceA-95">
        [95]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-96">
       <a href="#cite_note-96">
        [96]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-97">
       <a href="#cite_note-97">
        [97]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NYT062312_98-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NYT062312-98">
        [98]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of June 2012
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , the battery pack used modified
      <a href="/wiki/Panasonic" title="Panasonic">
       Panasonic
      </a>
      cells with nickel-cobalt-aluminum
      <a href="/wiki/Cathode" title="Cathode">
       cathodes
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-MT20120622_4-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-MT20120622-4">
        [4]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Each cell was of the 18650 form factor (i.e., an 18 mm diameter, 65 mm height cylinder), similar to the Panasonic NCR18650B cell that has an energy density of 265 Wh/kg.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-99">
       <a href="#cite_note-99">
        [99]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Analysts estimate battery cost to be around 21–22% of the car cost.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-100">
       <a href="#cite_note-100">
        [100]
       </a>
      </sup>
      List price for a replacement battery was
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$44,000
      </span>
      in February 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-noland-loss1_101-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-noland-loss1-101">
        [101]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The battery is guaranteed for eight years or 125,000 miles (200,000 km in metric countries) for the base model with the 60 kWh battery pack. The 85 kWh battery pack is guaranteed for eight years and unlimited miles.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TMOptions_102-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-TMOptions-102">
        [102]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-103">
       <a href="#cite_note-103">
        [103]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A poll among drivers indicate that accumulated battery loss steadies around 5% after 30,000 miles (50,000 km),
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-104">
       <a href="#cite_note-104">
        [104]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-eltk-degrade_74-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-eltk-degrade-74">
        [74]
       </a>
      </sup>
      decreasing further about 1% per additional 30,000 miles. Unlike Nissan, Tesla does not specify a limit for battery loss, but some early battery packs have been replaced.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-noland-loss1_101-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-noland-loss1-101">
        [101]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-105">
       <a href="#cite_note-105">
        [105]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      A separate battery replacement guarantee takes effect after the eighth year at a cost of
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$10,000
      </span>
      for the 60 kWh battery and
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$12,000
      </span>
      for the 85 kWh battery.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-106">
       <a href="#cite_note-106">
        [106]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In 2013, Tesla canceled a 40 kWh version of the car due to lack of demand, stating that only 4% of pre-orders were for the 40 kWh battery option. Customers who ordered this option instead received the 60 kWh pack, with charge software-limited to 40 kWh (139 miles, 224 km
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-107">
       <a href="#cite_note-107">
        [107]
       </a>
      </sup>
      ). It has the improved acceleration and top speed of the bigger pack and can be upgraded to use the full 60 kWh for
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$11,000
      </span>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-108">
       <a href="#cite_note-108">
        [108]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      On April 8, 2015, Tesla Motors discontinued the Model S 60, and replaced the base model with the Model S 70.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-109">
       <a href="#cite_note-109">
        [109]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In 2015, Tesla introduced a 70 kWh battery to replace the existing 60 kWh batteries and base 60 kWh Model S vehicles, as the 60 was low margin and not sufficiently welcomed by customers.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2015ecP8_110-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-2015ecP8-110">
        [110]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2015ecP9_111-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-2015ecP9-111">
        [111]
       </a>
      </sup>
      All 70 kWh cars can be had with rear-wheel drive or all wheel drive.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-112">
       <a href="#cite_note-112">
        [112]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The 60 was re-introduced in 2016 as a software-limited 75, upgradable to 75.
     </p>
     <p>
      In July 2015, Tesla introduced its 70, 90, 90D and P90D variants along with a "ludicrous mode" for the performance model. The P90D combines a front axle power of 259 horsepower (193 kW) and rear axle power of 503 horsepower (375 kW) to a total of 762 horsepower (568 kW), for a 0–60 mph time of 2.8 sec. The acceleration of the P90D can reach 1.1
      <a href="/wiki/G-force" title="G-force">
       g
      </a>
      , described by Tesla as "faster than falling".
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-autoblog20150715_75-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-autoblog20150715-75">
        [75]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The "ludicrous mode" costs
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$10,000
      </span>
      for P90D, but was discounted to
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$5,000
      </span>
      plus labor for P85D owners until January 2016.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-musk2015-07-17_113-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-musk2015-07-17-113">
        [113]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In July 2015, Tesla introduced its 90 and P90D, a "range upgrade" of the 85 variants with a 90 kWh battery and explained the 6% energy increase with "improved cell chemistry"
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-autoblog20150715_75-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-autoblog20150715-75">
        [75]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and with the introduction of
      <a href="/wiki/Silicon" title="Silicon">
       silicon
      </a>
      into the graphite cell
      <a href="/wiki/Anode" title="Anode">
       anode
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-114">
       <a href="#cite_note-114">
        [114]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla additionally announced its expectation of an annual improvement in battery capacity of about 5%. Tesla also explained that apart from the P90D the Model S has its main battery conductor protected by a
      <a href="/wiki/Fuse_(electrical)" title="Fuse (electrical)">
       fuse
      </a>
      rated for 1,300 A and that this rating is somewhat conservative given the uncertainty of the exact conditions under which a fuse melts. To reduce this uncertainty Tesla has for the P90D introduced
      <a href="/wiki/Inconel" title="Inconel">
       Inconel
      </a>
      battery contactors
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ludiInco_115-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ludiInco-115">
        [115]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and an electronically controlled pyro-activated fuse, which monitors the current at the millisecond level, cuts the power with "extreme precision and certainty" and has a rating of 1,500 A.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-autoblog20150715_75-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-autoblog20150715-75">
        [75]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_with_hood_up.JPG">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2376" data-file-width="2400" height="218" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Tesla_Model_S_with_hood_up.JPG/220px-Tesla_Model_S_with_hood_up.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Tesla_Model_S_with_hood_up.JPG/330px-Tesla_Model_S_with_hood_up.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Tesla_Model_S_with_hood_up.JPG/440px-Tesla_Model_S_with_hood_up.JPG 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_with_hood_up.JPG" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Tesla Model S showing the front trunk where the engine would be in a typical car. Tesla Motors calls this a
        <i>
         frunk
        </i>
        .
        <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TMspecs_116-0">
         <a href="#cite_note-TMspecs-116">
          [116]
         </a>
        </sup>
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      In February 2016, the 85 kWh battery option was discontinued in countries including the US, Australia and Canada.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-117">
       <a href="#cite_note-117">
        [117]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In March 2016, media reported that a firmware version distributed for the Tesla Model S has support for a yet to come P100D variant.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-118">
       <a href="#cite_note-118">
        [118]
       </a>
      </sup>
      This battery is more complicated to make than the 90 version.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-119">
       <a href="#cite_note-119">
        [119]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The P100D was released in August 2016.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-P100D_33-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-P100D-33">
        [33]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Practicality_and_livability">
       Practicality and livability
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Practicality and livability">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      The Model S is notable for being designed solely with an electric powertrain in mind, unlike other vehicles where the manufacturer has simply swapped out or supplanted an internal combustion engine with an electric motor.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-120">
       <a href="#cite_note-120">
        [120]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As a result, the Model S is able to offer unique features such as a front trunk, 'frunk', in addition to a spacious rear trunk (with a capacity of 894 liters) and a greatly enlarged front crumple zone compared to the typical combustion engine powered vehicle.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-auto1_84-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-auto1-84">
        [84]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      To enhance livability, Tesla has developed a network of fast-charging '
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_station" title="Tesla station">
       Supercharger' stations
      </a>
      that allow the driver to quickly and easily top-up the charge on their Model S.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-auto1_84-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-auto1-84">
        [84]
       </a>
      </sup>
      This Supercharger network has rapidly expanded in Europe, across the United States, and other countries where the there is significant demand, and as of September 2016
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , the network has been established in most American states, thus making cross-country and long distance trips in an electric vehicle feasible and greatly alleviating fears of range anxiety.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-auto1_84-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-auto1-84">
        [84]
       </a>
      </sup>
      See the
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Model_S#Supercharger" title="Tesla Model S">
       Supercharger
      </a>
      section below for further information.
     </p>
     <p>
      Researchers from the
      <a href="/wiki/University_of_California,_Davis" title="University of California, Davis">
       University of California, Davis
      </a>
      conducted a study to identify the factors influencing the decision to adopt high-end battery electric vehicles (BEV), such as the Tesla Model S, as these vehicles are remarkably different from mainstream BEVs. The 2016 study found that "
      <i>
       environmental, performance, and technological motivations are reasons for adoption; the new technology brings a new segment of buyers into the market; and financial purchase incentives are not important in the consumer’s decision to adopt a high-end BEV.
      </i>
      "
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-121">
       <a href="#cite_note-121">
        [121]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>

          <li id="cite_note-122">
           <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
            <b>
             <a href="#cite_ref-122">
              ^
             </a>
            </b>
           </span>
           <span class="reference-text">
            Original stated 40 kWh model specifications. Range limited 60 kWh versions actually delivered.
           </span>
          </li>
          <li id="cite_note-ludicrous-123">
           <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
            ^
            <a href="#cite_ref-ludicrous_123-0">
             <sup>
              <i>
               <b>
                a
               </b>
              </i>
             </sup>
            </a>
            <a href="#cite_ref-ludicrous_123-1">
             <sup>
              <i>
               <b>

               </b>
              </i>
             </sup>
            </a>
            <a href="#cite_ref-ludicrous_123-2">
             <sup>
              <i>
               <b>
                c
               </b>
              </i>
             </sup>
            </a>
           </span>
           <span class="reference-text">
            Only available for Dual-Motor Performance models with optional Ludicrous Mode upgrade, which requires 90 kWh battery for new cars (P90D). Only available until January 2016 for P85D already in ownership.
            <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-musk2015-07-17_113-1">
             <a href="#cite_note-musk2015-07-17-113">
              [113]
             </a>
            </sup>
           </span>
          </li>
          <li id="cite_note-motorpower-124">

     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Energy_consumption">
       Energy consumption
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Energy consumption">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      Under its five-cycle testing protocol, the US
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Environmental_Protection_Agency" title="Environmental Protection Agency">
       Environmental Protection Agency
      </a>
      (EPA) rated the 85 kWh Model S model with a combined
      <a href="/wiki/Fuel_economy_in_automobiles" title="Fuel economy in automobiles">
       fuel economy
      </a>
      equivalent of 89 MPGe (2.64 L/100 km), with an equivalent 88 mpg
      <sub>
       <small>
        -US
       </small>
      </sub>
      (2.7 L/100 km; 106 mpg
      <sub>
       <small>
        -imp
       </small>
      </sub>
      ) in city driving and 90 mpg
      <sub>
       <small>
        -US
       </small>
      </sub>
      (2.6 L/100 km; 110 mpg
      <sub>
       <small>
        -imp
       </small>
      </sub>
      ) on highways.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EPAratings_12-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-EPAratings-12">
        [12]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The following table shows the EPA's official ratings for fuel economy in
      <a href="/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent" title="Miles per gallon gasoline equivalent">
       miles per gallon gasoline equivalent
      </a>
      (MPGe) and EPA's estimated out-of-pocket fuel costs for the variants of the Model S rated as of 30 December 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and as displayed in the
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Monroney_label" title="Monroney label">
       Monroney label
      </a>
      .
     </p>

     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Battery_placement">
       Battery placement
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Battery placement">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      In contrast to most other
      <a href="/wiki/Battery_electric_vehicle" title="Battery electric vehicle">
       battery electric vehicles
      </a>
      including the
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Roadster" title="Tesla Roadster">
       Roadster
      </a>
      , the battery pack of the Model S forms the floor of the vehicle between the axles, providing the vehicle with several advantages. Most notably, since the battery pack is the single heaviest component of the vehicle, the Model S has a
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Center_of_gravity" title="Center of gravity">
       center of gravity
      </a>
      <a href="/wiki/Automobile_handling#Center_of_mass_height" title="Automobile handling">
       height
      </a>
      of only 18 inches (46 cm)
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-rope_91-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-rope-91">
        [91]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-sciAbuild_136-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-sciAbuild-136">
        [130]
       </a>
      </sup>
      (about the same as a
      <a href="/wiki/Lotus_Elise" title="Lotus Elise">
       Lotus Elise
      </a>
      ),
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-137">
       <a href="#cite_note-137">
        [131]
       </a>
      </sup>
      helping it to achieve a
      <a href="/wiki/Formula_One_car#Lateral_acceleration" title="Formula One car">
       lateral acceleration
      </a>
      of 0.9g
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-youtube_RWQ_dnpplaA_138-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-youtube_RWQ_dnpplaA-138">
        [132]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and good protection against
      <a href="/wiki/Rollover" title="Rollover">
       rollover
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-139">
       <a href="#cite_note-139">
        [133]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gcsafe_140-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-gcsafe-140">
        [134]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Secondly, the absence of a heavy engine between the front or rear axle allows the bulk of the
      <a href="/wiki/Mass_distribution" title="Mass distribution">
       mass to be centralized
      </a>
      between the axles, lowering
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Rotational_inertia" title="Rotational inertia">
       rotational inertia
      </a>
      allowing it to turn more quickly for its weight. Thirdly, the placement of the battery pack increases the
      <a href="/wiki/Anti-intrusion_bar" title="Anti-intrusion bar">
       rigidity of the passenger compartment
      </a>
      , improving the
      <a href="/wiki/Automobile_safety#Active_and_passive_safety" title="Automobile safety">
       passive safety
      </a>
      of the vehicle.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-141">
       <a href="#cite_note-141">
        [135]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Fourth, placing the battery pack under the vehicle makes it possible to remove or replace the entire unit in 90 seconds,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-142">
       <a href="#cite_note-142">
        [136]
       </a>
      </sup>
      either for maintenance or for Tesla's Battery Swap service.
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Charger">
       Charger
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Charger">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_Charing_port_2.jpg">

       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
