      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_store,_Austin,_Texas_05.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2448" data-file-width="3264" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Tesla_store%2C_Austin%2C_Texas_05.jpg/220px-Tesla_store%2C_Austin%2C_Texas_05.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Tesla_store%2C_Austin%2C_Texas_05.jpg/330px-Tesla_store%2C_Austin%2C_Texas_05.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Tesla_store%2C_Austin%2C_Texas_05.jpg/440px-Tesla_store%2C_Austin%2C_Texas_05.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_store,_Austin,_Texas_05.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Model S charging connectors at the Tesla store in
        <a href="/wiki/Austin,_Texas" title="Austin, Texas">
         Austin, Texas
        </a>
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      In all markets the charge port is located behind a door in the left taillight. During charging, the charge port pulses green. The frequency at which the charge port's light pulses slows down as the charge level approaches full. When charging is complete, the light stops pulsing and is solid green.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-143">
       <a href="#cite_note-143">
        [137]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The Model S comes equipped with a different charger and connector in North American versus other markets, derived from differences in the local electric grid systems.
     </p>
     <h4>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="North_America">
       North America
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: North America">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h4>
     <p>
      The standard North American onboard charger accepts single phase 120 or 240-volt sources at a rate of up to
      <span class="nowrap">
       10 kW
      </span>
      . Included adapters allow the car to charge from a standard 120 volt outlet, a 240 volt NEMA 14-50 outlet, and
      <a href="/wiki/SAE_J1772" title="SAE J1772">
       SAE J1772
      </a>
      public chargers. An optional
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$2,000
      </span>
      upgrade for a second
      <span class="nowrap">
       10 kW
      </span>
      onboard charger supports a total of up to
      <span class="nowrap">
       20 kW
      </span>
      charging from an
      <span class="nowrap">
       80 amp
      </span>
      available
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$750
      </span>
      Tesla Wall Connector.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-MT20120622_4-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-MT20120622-4">
        [4]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The North American connector uses a proprietary Tesla design.
     </p>
     <p>
      Charging times vary depending on the battery pack's state-of-charge, its overall capacity, the available voltage, and the available
      <a href="/wiki/Circuit_breaker" title="Circuit breaker">
       circuit breaker
      </a>
      amperage. From a 120 volt/15 amp household outlet, the range increases by 3.75 miles (6 km) for every hour of charging. From a
      <span class="nowrap">
       10 kW
      </span>
      ,
      <a href="/wiki/AC_power_plugs_and_sockets#NEMA_14-50" title="AC power plugs and sockets">
       NEMA 14–50
      </a>
      240 V/50 A outlet (like those used by
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/RVs" title="RVs">
       RVs
      </a>
      or standard cooking ranges), the charge rate is 28.75 miles (46 km) per hour. Using Tesla's
      <span class="nowrap">
       20 kW
      </span>
      ,
      <span class="nowrap">
       240 V
      </span>
      High Power Wall Connector increases the rate to 57 miles (92 km) per hour if the car is configured with dual chargers (
      <span class="nowrap">
       20 kW
      </span>
      ).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TMCharging_144-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-TMCharging-144">
        [138]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h4>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Europe_.2F_Asia_Pacific">
       Europe / Asia Pacific
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Europe / Asia Pacific">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h4>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla-type-2-model-s-charge-port-inlet-0996.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1664" data-file-width="2496" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Tesla-type-2-model-s-charge-port-inlet-0996.jpg/220px-Tesla-type-2-model-s-charge-port-inlet-0996.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Tesla-type-2-model-s-charge-port-inlet-0996.jpg/330px-Tesla-type-2-model-s-charge-port-inlet-0996.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Tesla-type-2-model-s-charge-port-inlet-0996.jpg/440px-Tesla-type-2-model-s-charge-port-inlet-0996.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla-type-2-model-s-charge-port-inlet-0996.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Type 2-compatible inlet on European Model S
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      The standard European charger accepts three phase
      <span class="nowrap">
       230 V
      </span>
      or
      <span class="nowrap">
       400 V
      </span>
      at up to
      <span class="nowrap">
       11 kW
      </span>
      . The
      <a href="/wiki/Type_2_connector" title="Type 2 connector">
       Type 2 connector
      </a>
      on the car directly accepts "Mennekes"
      <a href="/wiki/IEC_62196" title="IEC 62196">
       IEC 62196
      </a>
      charging from public stations at up to 400 V, and included adapters allow the car to charge from standard continental European outlets and
      <a href="/wiki/IEC_60309" title="IEC 60309">
       IEC 60309
      </a>
      230 volt (blue 3-pin) or 400 volt (red 5-pin) outlets, depending on region. The addition of a second charger supports charging at up to 22 kW, providing up to 70 miles (110 km) of range per hour of charge; the Tesla Wall Connector is expected to be available in the second quarter of 2016.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-145">
       <a href="#cite_note-145">
        [139]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla-type-2-supercharger-outlet-1004.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1664" data-file-width="2496" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Tesla-type-2-supercharger-outlet-1004.jpg/220px-Tesla-type-2-supercharger-outlet-1004.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Tesla-type-2-supercharger-outlet-1004.jpg/330px-Tesla-type-2-supercharger-outlet-1004.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Tesla-type-2-supercharger-outlet-1004.jpg/440px-Tesla-type-2-supercharger-outlet-1004.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla-type-2-supercharger-outlet-1004.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Type 2-compatible outlet found on
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Tesla_supercharger" title="Tesla supercharger">
         Tesla superchargers
        </a>
        in Europe
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Suspension">
       Suspension
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Suspension">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      The Model S has
      <a href="/wiki/Independent_suspension" title="Independent suspension">
       independent
      </a>
      <a href="/wiki/Coil_spring" title="Coil spring">
       coil spring
      </a>
      suspension on all four wheels –  front
      <a href="/wiki/Double_wishbone_suspension" title="Double wishbone suspension">
       double wishbone
      </a>
      , virtual steer axis
      <a href="/wiki/Control_arm" title="Control arm">
       control arm
      </a>
      and rear independent
      <a href="/wiki/Multi-link_suspension" title="Multi-link suspension">
       multilink
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-model_s_specs_63-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-model_s_specs-63">
        [63]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As an extra-cost option, the car is available with
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Self-leveling_suspension" title="Self-leveling suspension">
       self-leveling
      </a>
      ,
      <a href="/wiki/Height_adjustable_suspension" title="Height adjustable suspension">
       height-adjustable
      </a>
      <a href="/wiki/Air_suspension" title="Air suspension">
       air suspension
      </a>
      . This is accomplished via adjustable Bilstein shock absorbers controlled by the driver. The car is meant to lower itself at highway speed and raise itself to traverse steep driveways and rough terrain, despite the low 6-inch
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Ground_clearance" title="Ground clearance">
       ground clearance
      </a>
      and rather long 116-inch wheelbase.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-146">
       <a href="#cite_note-146">
        [140]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Because, in the Tesla, electronic systems can be upgraded by "over-the-air" download, rather than recall, the suspension system has been changed retroactively on several occasions. During the 2013 'fire investigation',
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/NHTSA" title="NHTSA">
       NHTSA
      </a>
      asked Tesla to disable the car's ability to lower itself at speed on the theory that a ground clearance below 6 inches might cause the batteries underneath the car to contact road debris.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-147">
       <a href="#cite_note-147">
        [141]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In September 2014, Tesla upgraded the
      <a href="/wiki/Height_adjustable_suspension" title="Height adjustable suspension">
       height adjustment feature
      </a>
      for Model S cars equipped with air suspension to remember locations that require higher clearance such as those with potholes and steep driveways, and automatically adjusts to avoid them.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-148">
       <a href="#cite_note-148">
        [142]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Autopilot">
       Autopilot
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Autopilot">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <div class="hatnote" role="note">
      Main article:
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Autopilot" title="Tesla Autopilot">
       Tesla Autopilot
      </a>
     </div>
     <div class="hatnote" role="note">
      See also:
      <a href="/wiki/Autonomous_car" title="Autonomous car">
       Autonomous car
      </a>
      and
      <a href="/wiki/Connected_car" title="Connected car">
       Connected car
      </a>
     </div>
     <p>
      Beginning in late September 2014, all new Model S vehicles come equipped with a camera (supplied by
      <a href="/wiki/Mobileye" title="Mobileye">
       Mobileye
      </a>
      ) mounted at the top of the windshield, forward looking radar (supplied by
      <a href="/wiki/Robert_Bosch_GmbH" title="Robert Bosch GmbH">
       Bosch
      </a>
      )
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-149">
       <a href="#cite_note-149">
        [143]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-150">
       <a href="#cite_note-150">
        [144]
       </a>
      </sup>
      in the lower grill, and ultrasonic
      <a href="/wiki/Acoustic_location" title="Acoustic location">
       acoustic location
      </a>
      sensors in the front and rear bumpers that provide a 360-degree buffer zone around the car. This equipment allows Model S to detect road signs, lane markings, obstacles, and other vehicles. In addition to
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Adaptive_cruise_control" title="Adaptive cruise control">
       adaptive cruise control
      </a>
      and
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Lane_departure_warning" title="Lane departure warning">
       lane departure warning
      </a>
      , a
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$2,500
      </span>
      "Tech Package" option will allow this system to enable semi-autonomous drive and parking capabilities.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-151">
       <a href="#cite_note-151">
        [145]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-152">
       <a href="#cite_note-152">
        [146]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-153">
       <a href="#cite_note-153">
        [147]
       </a>
      </sup>
      All Model S sold since October 2014 have the option to have Autopilot, which allows limited
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Hands-free_driving" title="Hands-free driving">
       hands-free driving
      </a>
      . AutoPilot-enabled cars receive software updates for the AutoPilot software wirelessly, just as all other Model S cars receive general software updates wirelessly.
     </p>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_Hwy_40.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1509" data-file-width="2263" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Tesla_Model_S_Hwy_40.jpg/220px-Tesla_Model_S_Hwy_40.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Tesla_Model_S_Hwy_40.jpg/330px-Tesla_Model_S_Hwy_40.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Tesla_Model_S_Hwy_40.jpg/440px-Tesla_Model_S_Hwy_40.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_Hwy_40.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Some people agreed that Tesla Autopilot can reduce accidents due negligence and fatigue in long range drive use.
        <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-154">
         <a href="#cite_note-154">
          [148]
         </a>
        </sup>
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      According to Elon Musk, the Model S was designed to be a computer on wheels: "We really designed the Model S to be a very sophisticated computer on wheels. Tesla is a software company as much as it is a hardware company. A huge part of what Tesla is, is a Silicon Valley software company. We view this the same as updating your phone or your laptop."
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-155">
       <a href="#cite_note-155">
        [149]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Full autonomy is “really a software limitation: The hardware exists to create full autonomy, so it’s really about developing advanced,
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Narrow_AI" title="Narrow AI">
       narrow AI
      </a>
      for the car to operate on.“
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-156">
       <a href="#cite_note-156">
        [150]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-157">
       <a href="#cite_note-157">
        [151]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Tesla's autonomous driving features are ahead of production cars, and its Autopilot can be classified as somewhere between levels 2 and 3 under the
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/U.S._Department_of_Transportation" title="U.S. Department of Transportation">
       U.S. Department of Transportation
      </a>
      ’s
      <a href="/wiki/National_Highway_Traffic_Safety_Administration" title="National Highway Traffic Safety Administration">
       National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
      </a>
      (NHTSA)
      <a href="/wiki/Autonomous_car#Classification" title="Autonomous car">
       five levels of vehicle automation
      </a>
      . At this level, the car can act autonomously but requires the full attention of the driver, who must be prepared to take control at a moment's notice.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-158">
       <a href="#cite_note-158">
        [152]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-159">
       <a href="#cite_note-159">
        [153]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-160">
       <a href="#cite_note-160">
        [154]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Autopilot is suitable only on
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Limited-access_highway" title="Limited-access highway">
       limited-access highways
      </a>
      , and sometimes it will fail to detect lane markings and disengage itself. In urban driving the system will not read traffic signals or obey stop signs. The system also does not detect pedestrians or cyclists.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-HwyOnly_161-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-HwyOnly-161">
        [155]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Starting October 2016, all Tesla cars are built with the necessary hardware to allow full self-driving capability at a safety level (
      <a href="/wiki/SAE_International" title="SAE International">
       SAE Level 5
      </a>
      ).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TeslaLevel5_162-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-TeslaLevel5-162">
        [156]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The system will operate in "shadow mode" (processing without taking action) and send data back to Tesla to improve its abilities until the software is ready for deployment via over-the-air upgrades.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-geuss_163-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-geuss-163">
        [157]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla Motors says it expects to enable full self-driving by the end of 2017, after proper testing.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TeslaLevel5_162-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-TeslaLevel5-162">
        [156]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h4>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Fatal_accident">
       Fatal accident
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Fatal accident">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h4>
     <p>
      The first known fatal accident involving a Tesla Model S when the car was in autopilot mode took place in
      <a href="/wiki/Williston,_Florida" title="Williston, Florida">
       Williston, Florida
      </a>
      on 7 May 2016. The driver was killed in a crash with a large 18-wheel
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Tractor-trailer" title="Tractor-trailer">
       tractor-trailer
      </a>
      . By late June 2016 the U.S.
      <a href="/wiki/National_Highway_Traffic_Safety_Administration" title="National Highway Traffic Safety Administration">
       National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
      </a>
      (NHTSA) opened a formal investigation into the accident working with the
      <a href="/wiki/Florida_Highway_Patrol" title="Florida Highway Patrol">
       Florida Highway Patrol
      </a>
      . According to the NHTSA, preliminary reports indicate the crash occurred when the tractor-trailer made a left turn in front of the Tesla at an intersection on a non-controlled access highway, and the car failed to apply the brakes. The car continued to travel after passing under the truck’s trailer.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-AutopilotCrash01_164-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-AutopilotCrash01-164">
        [158]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-AutopilotCrash02_165-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-AutopilotCrash02-165">
        [159]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-AutopilotCrash03_166-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-AutopilotCrash03-166">
        [160]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The NHTSA's preliminary evaluation was opened to examine the design and performance of any automated driving systems in use at the time of the crash, which involves a population of an estimated 25,000 Model S cars.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-167">
       <a href="#cite_note-167">
        [161]
       </a>
      </sup>
      On 8 July 2016, the NHTSA requested Tesla Motors to hand over to the agency detailed information about the design, operation and testing of its Autopilot technology. The agency also requested details of all design changes and updates to Autopilot since its introduction, and Tesla's planned updates scheduled for the next four months.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-168">
       <a href="#cite_note-168">
        [162]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      According to Tesla, "neither autopilot nor the driver noticed the white side of the tractor-trailer against a brightly lit sky, so the brake was not applied." The car attempted to drive full speed under the trailer, "with the bottom of the trailer impacting the windshield of the Model S." Tesla also stated that this was Tesla’s first known autopilot death in over 130 million miles (208 million km) driven by its customers where Autopilot was activated. According to Tesla there is a fatality every 94 million miles (150 million km) among all type of vehicles in the U.S.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-AutopilotCrash01_164-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-AutopilotCrash01-164">
        [158]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-AutopilotCrash02_165-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-AutopilotCrash02-165">
        [159]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-169">
       <a href="#cite_note-169">
        [163]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Some statisticians say that Tesla's use of statistics is meaningless due to the relatively small total distance traveled by Tesla cars and the different driving conditions of the two data sets being compared. It is estimated that billions of miles will need to be traveled before a statistically significant comparison can be made. Researchers say that Tesla and others need to release more data on the limitations and performance of automated driving systems if self-driving cars are to become safe and understood enough for mass market use.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-170">
       <a href="#cite_note-170">
        [164]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Instrument_panel">
       Instrument panel
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Instrument panel">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_digital_panels.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="3000" data-file-width="4000" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/Tesla_Model_S_digital_panels.jpg/220px-Tesla_Model_S_digital_panels.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/Tesla_Model_S_digital_panels.jpg/330px-Tesla_Model_S_digital_panels.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/Tesla_Model_S_digital_panels.jpg/440px-Tesla_Model_S_digital_panels.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_digital_panels.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Production dashboard with main dashboard digital display (left) and central 17-inch (430 mm)
        <a href="/wiki/Touchscreen" title="Touchscreen">
         touchscreen
        </a>
        control panel (right)
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      The instrument panel is a 12.3-inch (31 cm)
      <a href="/wiki/Liquid-crystal_display" title="Liquid-crystal display">
       liquid-crystal display
      </a>
      <a href="/wiki/Electronic_instrument_cluster" title="Electronic instrument cluster">
       electronic instrument cluster
      </a>
      that indicates speed, power usage, charge level, estimated range and active gear, as well as Nav directions (driven by
      <a href="/wiki/Garmin" title="Garmin">
       Garmin
      </a>
      ). The gearbox can be set to Drive, Neutral, Reverse and Park. The
      <a href="/wiki/Infotainment" title="Infotainment">
       infotainment
      </a>
      control
      <a href="/wiki/Touchscreen" title="Touchscreen">
       touchscreen
      </a>
      is a 17-inch (43 cm)
      <a href="/wiki/Multi-touch" title="Multi-touch">
       multi-touch
      </a>
      panel divided into four areas. A top line displays status symbols and provides shortcuts to Charging,
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/HomeLink" title="HomeLink">
       HomeLink
      </a>
      , Driver Profiles, vehicle information (software version and the
      <a href="/wiki/Vehicle_identification_number" title="Vehicle identification number">
       Vehicle identification number
      </a>
      ) and
      <a href="/wiki/Bluetooth" title="Bluetooth">
       Bluetooth
      </a>
      . The second line provides access to several apps including Media, Nav (driven by
      <a href="/wiki/Google_Maps" title="Google Maps">
       Google Maps
      </a>
      , and thus is separate from the Nav on instrument panel), Energy, Web, Camera and Phone. The central main viewing area displays the (two) active apps, subdivided into upper and lower areas. (Most apps can be expanded to take up the entire area). At the bottom is access to various controls and settings for the vehicle such as doors, locks and lights as well as temperature controls and a secondary volume control.
     </p>
     <p>
      The instrument cluster and the infotainment panel are driven by separate
      <a href="/wiki/Nvidia" title="Nvidia">
       Nvidia
      </a>
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Tegra_3" title="Tegra 3">
       Tegra 3
      </a>
      <a href="/wiki/3D_computer_graphics" title="3D computer graphics">
       3D Visual Computing
      </a>
      Modules.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-171">
       <a href="#cite_note-171">
        [165]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-172">
       <a href="#cite_note-172">
        [166]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla was the first company to ship this technology. (
      <a href="/wiki/Audi" title="Audi">
       Audi
      </a>
      later delivered this technology in its 2013 model year in Europe, and in North America in 2014.)
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-173">
       <a href="#cite_note-173">
        [167]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Tegra
      <a href="/wiki/System_on_a_chip" title="System on a chip">
       system on a chip
      </a>
      (SoC) integrates eight specialized processors, including a
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Multi-core" title="Multi-core">
       multi-core
      </a>
      <a href="/wiki/ARM_architecture" title="ARM architecture">
       ARM
      </a>
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/CPU" title="CPU">
       CPU
      </a>
      , a
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/GPU" title="GPU">
       GPU
      </a>
      , and dedicated audio, video and image processors. Nvidia claimed that it consumes 2% of the energy of a typical CPU.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-174">
       <a href="#cite_note-174">
        [168]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The navigation system uses
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/GPS" title="GPS">
       GPS
      </a>
      and a mix of Garmin and Google Maps route guidance. The map display on the 17-inch screen requires a constant Internet connection, so navigation is limited in areas without mobile network coverage. The Nav on the instrument panel is loaded on the car and does not need Internet access to function.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-175">
       <a href="#cite_note-175">
        [169]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Update 6.2 features automatic nav guidance to charging stations if range is insufficient.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-176">
       <a href="#cite_note-176">
        [170]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Enthusiasts have developed the Open Vehicle Monitoring System (
      <a href="/wiki/OVMS" title="OVMS">
       OVMS
      </a>
      ) which allows the owner to remotely observe a variety of different vehicle operating parameters, such as battery state of charge, typically using a
      <a href="/wiki/Smartphone" title="Smartphone">
       smartphone
      </a>
      . Some switchgear used are Mercedes parts, such as window switches, cruise control lever, and drive selector.
     </p>
     <p>
      According to Elon Musk, the Model S runs on the open-source
      <a href="/wiki/Linux" title="Linux">
       Linux
      </a>
      <a href="/wiki/Operating_system" title="Operating system">
       operating system
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2015shareholdermeeting_177-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-2015shareholdermeeting-177">
        [171]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In 2014 Autoblog reported that Tesla Models S owners had determined via the car's combined
      <a href="/wiki/On-board_diagnostics" title="On-board diagnostics">
       diagnostics
      </a>
      and
      <a href="/wiki/Ethernet" title="Ethernet">
       Ethernet
      </a>
      port that a
      <a href="/wiki/Ubuntu_(operating_system)" title="Ubuntu (operating system)">
       Ubuntu
      </a>
      system controlling the central touchscreen is connected to the car's internal Ethernet.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-178">
       <a href="#cite_note-178">
        [172]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The same users determined that another Ubuntu system controlling the dashboard/navigation screen also is connected to the internal network, together with a third computer of unknown type with an unknown function.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-179">
       <a href="#cite_note-179">
        [173]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Features">
       Features
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Features">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_rear_child_seats_(2).jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2124" data-file-width="3186" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9f/Tesla_Model_S_rear_child_seats_%282%29.jpg/220px-Tesla_Model_S_rear_child_seats_%282%29.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9f/Tesla_Model_S_rear_child_seats_%282%29.jpg/330px-Tesla_Model_S_rear_child_seats_%282%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9f/Tesla_Model_S_rear_child_seats_%282%29.jpg/440px-Tesla_Model_S_rear_child_seats_%282%29.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_rear_child_seats_(2).jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        The Model S has an optional folding third row with rear-facing seats for two children secured with a racing-style five-point harness.
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_Key_(8406842279).jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2448" data-file-width="3264" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Tesla_Model_S_Key_%288406842279%29.jpg/220px-Tesla_Model_S_Key_%288406842279%29.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Tesla_Model_S_Key_%288406842279%29.jpg/330px-Tesla_Model_S_Key_%288406842279%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Tesla_Model_S_Key_%288406842279%29.jpg/440px-Tesla_Model_S_Key_%288406842279%29.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_Key_(8406842279).jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        The Model S key
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      All versions of the Model S have the same body and normally seat five passengers. An optional folding third row for
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$2,500
      </span>
      becomes a rear-facing two-place child seat. The option includes a stronger rear bumper.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-sciAbuild_136-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-sciAbuild-136">
        [130]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gcsafe_140-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-gcsafe-140">
        [134]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Each third row seat has a racing-style five-point harness for passengers over 37 in (0.94 m) tall and weighing between 35 to 77 lb (16 to 35 kg). Cargo space is available under the front hood (which Tesla called a "frunk," a
      <a href="/wiki/Portmanteau" title="Portmanteau">
       portmanteau
      </a>
      of "front trunk.") The optional third row gives the greatest passenger capacity of any electric vehicle.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-180">
       <a href="#cite_note-180">
        [174]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In October 2014, the upgraded Model S P85D, D for dual, was introduced.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-181">
       <a href="#cite_note-181">
        [175]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The upgraded version features two electric motors, one driving the rear wheels as in prior versions, and one driving the front wheels. Safety features are enhanced also, for example with partial auto-pilot functions. The dual motor version will be available also for the basic 85 kWh versions for around
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$4,000
      </span>
      more in price. The rear wheel drive version of the P85 was removed, and the dual motor option is not available for the 60 kWh version.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-David_Noland_79-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-David_Noland-79">
        [79]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The 2015 model year update introduced
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Electromechanical_brake" title="Electromechanical brake">
       electromechanical brakes
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-182">
       <a href="#cite_note-182">
        [176]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In 2016, the 85kWh and later 90kWh battery was discontinued from all markets. A glass roof with no horizontal roof bar between the
      <a href="/wiki/Pillar_(car)" title="Pillar (car)">
       B-pillars
      </a>
      was introduced in late 2016.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-183">
       <a href="#cite_note-183">
        [177]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Vehicle_warranty_and_maintenance">
       Vehicle warranty and maintenance
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Vehicle warranty and maintenance">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      The Model S is covered by a 4-year, 50,000 mi (80,000 km) limited warranty,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-teslaspecs_184-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-teslaspecs-184">
        [178]
       </a>
      </sup>
      that includes all standard equipment, the transmission and the complete powertrain (excluding tires).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-teslaservice_185-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-teslaservice-185">
        [179]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The warranty can be extended an additional 4 years or 50,000 miles (80,000 km) beyond the original terms for
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$4,000
      </span>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-teslaservice_185-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-teslaservice-185">
        [179]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Warranty coverage includes a complementary loaner car—a Performance 85 or Tesla Roadster—when service is required.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-teslablog_186-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-teslablog-186">
        [180]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In April 2013, Tesla announced that a previously mandatory
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$600
      </span>
      annual vehicle inspection and maintenance fee would be made optional, and would not be required to maintain warranty coverage.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-teslablog_186-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-teslablog-186">
        [180]
       </a>
      </sup>
      If chosen, the fee covers a complete inspection, tire alignment, new brake pads, hardware upgrades and miscellaneous other maintenance items as needed.
     </p>
     <p>
      The battery and drive unit are covered for eight years or 125,000 miles (200,000 km in metric countries) for the 60 kWh base model, or eight years and unlimited distance for all 70 and 85 kWh models.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TMOptions_102-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-TMOptions-102">
        [102]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NAwarranty_187-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NAwarranty-187">
        [181]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The unconditional battery warranty covers everything except deliberate damage, even including user error.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CNNmoney_188-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-CNNmoney-188">
        [182]
       </a>
      </sup>
      However, loss of battery capacity over time or usage is not covered under warranty.
      <sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">
       [
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title="Wikipedia:Please clarify">
         <span title="how does it differ from warranty – percentage of allowable degradation? (March 2015)">
          clarification needed
         </span>
        </a>
       </i>
       ]
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NAwarranty_187-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-NAwarranty-187">
        [181]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-QuickGuide_189-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-QuickGuide-189">
        [183]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Environmental_footprint">
       Environmental footprint
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Environmental footprint">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      In February 2014, the Automotive Science Group (ASG) published the result of a study conducted to
      <a href="/wiki/Life-cycle_assessment" title="Life-cycle assessment">
       assess the life-cycle
      </a>
      of over 1,300 automobiles across nine categories sold in North America. The study ranked the Model S as the best environmental performer in the 2014
      <a href="/wiki/Full-size_car" title="Full-size car">
       full-size cars
      </a>
      category.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-190">
       <a href="#cite_note-190">
        [184]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Based on the assessment of life-cycle environmental footprint, the study concluded that the increased environmental impacts of manufacturing the vehicle are more than offset with increased environmental performance during operation. For the assessment, the study used the average electricity mix of the U.S. grid in 2014. The
      <a href="/wiki/Nissan_Leaf" title="Nissan Leaf">
       Nissan Leaf
      </a>
      had the smallest life-cycle environmental footprint of any model year 2014 automobile available in the North American market.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-191">
       <a href="#cite_note-191">
        [185]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In 2015, the
      <a href="/wiki/Union_of_Concerned_Scientists" title="Union of Concerned Scientists">
       Union of Concerned Scientists
      </a>
      found that in the US regions where the Model S is popular, the 68% higher manufacturing emissions are offset within a few years of average driving. During their life-cycle, EVs emit about half the amount of comparable fossil cars.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-UCS2015_192-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-UCS2015-192">
        [186]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-193">
       <a href="#cite_note-193">
        [187]
       </a>
      </sup>
      According to an
      <a href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">
       IBM
      </a>
      researcher, this analysis is the best available.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-194">
       <a href="#cite_note-194">
        [188]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Tesla has worked with ToxCo/Kinsbursky in the US since 2008 and
      <a href="/wiki/Umicore" title="Umicore">
       Umicore
      </a>
      in Europe
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-195">
       <a href="#cite_note-195">
        [189]
       </a>
      </sup>
      to
      <a href="/wiki/Battery_recycling#Lithium_ion_batteries" title="Battery recycling">
       recycle
      </a>
      worn out
      <a href="/wiki/Restriction_of_Hazardous_Substances_Directive" title="Restriction of Hazardous Substances Directive">
       RoHS
      </a>
      batteries,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-196">
       <a href="#cite_note-196">
        [190]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-197">
       <a href="#cite_note-197">
        [191]
       </a>
      </sup>
      which will be performed in
      <a href="/wiki/Gigafactory_1" title="Gigafactory 1">
       Gigafactory 1
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-198">
       <a href="#cite_note-198">
        [192]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h2>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Tesla_stations">
       Tesla stations
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Tesla stations">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h2>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Charging_Tesla_Model_S_01.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="3456" data-file-width="5184" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fd/Charging_Tesla_Model_S_01.jpg/220px-Charging_Tesla_Model_S_01.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fd/Charging_Tesla_Model_S_01.jpg/330px-Charging_Tesla_Model_S_01.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fd/Charging_Tesla_Model_S_01.jpg/440px-Charging_Tesla_Model_S_01.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Charging_Tesla_Model_S_01.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Tesla Model S charging at the Supercharger network station in
        <a href="/wiki/Newark,_Delaware" title="Newark, Delaware">
         Newark, Delaware
        </a>
        , United States
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Blue_Tesla_Model_S_Zoutelande_dunes_Holland.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1316" data-file-width="2027" height="143" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Blue_Tesla_Model_S_Zoutelande_dunes_Holland.jpg/220px-Blue_Tesla_Model_S_Zoutelande_dunes_Holland.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Blue_Tesla_Model_S_Zoutelande_dunes_Holland.jpg/330px-Blue_Tesla_Model_S_Zoutelande_dunes_Holland.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Blue_Tesla_Model_S_Zoutelande_dunes_Holland.jpg/440px-Blue_Tesla_Model_S_Zoutelande_dunes_Holland.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Blue_Tesla_Model_S_Zoutelande_dunes_Holland.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Tesla Model S charging at a public charging station in
        <a href="/wiki/Zoutelande" title="Zoutelande">
         Zoutelande
        </a>
        , the Netherlands
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <div class="hatnote" role="note">
      Main article:
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_station" title="Tesla station">
       Tesla station
      </a>
     </div>
     <p>
      In 2012, Tesla began building a network of 480-volt
      <a href="/wiki/Charging_station" title="Charging station">
       charging stations
      </a>
      to facilitate long-distance travel. In June 2013 Tesla announced that existing and future stations would become
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_station" title="Tesla station">
       Tesla stations
      </a>
      , with facilities to support under-two-minute battery pack swaps. As of early October 2014, 115 stations were operating in the United States, 71 in Europe and 23 in Asia.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-USModelS18K_199-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-USModelS18K-199">
        [193]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla_Motors_Supercharger_200-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla_Motors_Supercharger-200">
        [194]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Tesla network is usable only by Tesla vehicles, which are engineered for compatibility.
     </p>
     <p>
      The first Supercharger corridor opened in October 2012, with six stations placed along routes connecting San Francisco,
      <a href="/wiki/Lake_Tahoe" title="Lake Tahoe">
       Lake Tahoe
      </a>
      , Los Angeles and
      <a href="/wiki/Las_Vegas" title="Las Vegas">
       Las Vegas
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-GCC092512_201-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-GCC092512-201">
        [195]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-HC121012_202-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-HC121012-202">
        [196]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A second corridor opened in December 2012 connecting Washington, D.C., New York City, and
      <a href="/wiki/Boston" title="Boston">
       Boston
      </a>
      ; it includes three stations located in highway rest areas in
      <a href="/wiki/Delaware" title="Delaware">
       Delaware
      </a>
      and
      <a href="/wiki/Connecticut" title="Connecticut">
       Connecticut
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NYT122112_203-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NYT122112-203">
        [197]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The first Tesla stations in Europe opened in Norway in August 2013.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SuperchargerNor_204-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-SuperchargerNor-204">
        [198]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla next focused on Germany and the Netherlands, with plans to cover both countries by mid-2014. Switzerland, Belgium, Austria, Denmark and Luxembourg were to be covered by the end of 2014. Stations were to be within 200 mi (320 km) for about 90% of the population in France, England, Wales and Sweden by the end of 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-3Q2013Report_205-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-3Q2013Report-205">
        [199]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Supercharger">
       Supercharger
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Supercharger">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      The Supercharger is a proprietary DC rapid-charging station that provides up to 135 kW of power, giving 85 kWh vehicles an additional 180 mi (290 km) of range in about 15–30 minutes. Older 60 kWh may have reduced charge rate.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-206">
       <a href="#cite_note-206">
        [200]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In the West Coast corridor the Superchargers's grid access is assisted by a
      <a href="/wiki/Solar_panel" title="Solar panel">
       solar
      </a>
      <a href="/wiki/Carport" title="Carport">
       carport
      </a>
      system (some including a battery of a few hundred kWh)
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ingSup_207-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ingSup-207">
        [201]
       </a>
      </sup>
      provided by
      <a href="/wiki/SolarCity" title="SolarCity">
       SolarCity
      </a>
      . Eventually, all Tesla stations will be assisted by solar power.
     </p>
     <p>
      Supercharging hardware is now a standard on all vehicles sold by Tesla Motors. The Roadster is not compatible.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-GCC092512_201-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-GCC092512-201">
        [195]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-HC121012_202-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-HC121012-202">
        [196]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NYT122112_203-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-NYT122112-203">
        [197]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In early November 2013, Tesla reported that 90% of its customers had opted for supercharging capability.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-3Q2013Report_205-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-3Q2013Report-205">
        [199]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of April 2016
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , there are over 620 open superchargers around the world. Elon Musk said at the unveiling of the Model 3 that that number would be doubled by the end of 2017. Tesla has received criticism about the length of time it has taken them to install chargers on high use corridors of the United States such as I-40 and I-80.
      <sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">
       [
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">
         <span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (April 2016)">
          citation needed
         </span>
        </a>
       </i>
       ]
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Tesla built 120 kW
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TMSuperchargerPower_208-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-TMSuperchargerPower-208">
        [202]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Tesla_supercharger" title="Tesla supercharger">
       Tesla supercharger
      </a>
      stations to allow long distance travel in North America, Europe, Asia, and Australia.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TMSuperCharger_209-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-TMSuperCharger-209">
        [203]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A Supercharger can add up to 125 miles (201 km) of range in 20 minutes and a full charge in approximately one hour assuming a nearly empty
      <span class="nowrap">
       85 kWh
      </span>
      battery.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-MT20120622_4-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-MT20120622-4">
        [4]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TMCharging_144-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-TMCharging-144">
        [138]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Supercharging hardware is included in the 85 kWh, 70 kWh, and 60 kWh battery packs; in both the 85 kWh models and 70 kWh models,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-210">
       <a href="#cite_note-210">
        [204]
       </a>
      </sup>
      the payment for the car includes supercharging by default, but in the 60 kWh, supercharging was software-disabled and one must pay an extra fee to enable supercharging.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TMOptions_102-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-TMOptions-102">
        [102]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TMCharging_144-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-TMCharging-144">
        [138]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TMGear_211-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-TMGear-211">
        [205]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-212">
       <a href="#cite_note-212">
        [206]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Battery_swapping">
       Battery swapping
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: Battery swapping">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      Tesla designed its Model S to allow fast battery swapping, which also facilitates vehicle assembly.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-213">
       <a href="#cite_note-213">
        [207]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In June 2013, Tesla announced their goal to deploy a
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Battery_swapping" title="Battery swapping">
       battery swapping
      </a>
      station in Tesla stations. At a demonstration Tesla showed a battery swap operation taking just over 90 seconds, about half the time it takes to refill an empty gas tank.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Swapping01_214-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Swapping01-214">
        [208]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Swapping02_215-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Swapping02-215">
        [209]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <div class="thumb tleft">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_charging_station_with_solar_collector_trimmed.jpeg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1044" data-file-width="3120" height="100" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Tesla_charging_station_with_solar_collector_trimmed.jpeg/300px-Tesla_charging_station_with_solar_collector_trimmed.jpeg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Tesla_charging_station_with_solar_collector_trimmed.jpeg/450px-Tesla_charging_station_with_solar_collector_trimmed.jpeg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Tesla_charging_station_with_solar_collector_trimmed.jpeg/600px-Tesla_charging_station_with_solar_collector_trimmed.jpeg 2x" width="300"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_charging_station_with_solar_collector_trimmed.jpeg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Panoramic view of Tesla Supercharger rapid charging station in
        <a href="/wiki/Tejon,_California" title="Tejon, California">
         Tejon Ranch, California
        </a>
        .
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      Battery swapping was to be deployed along
      <a href="/wiki/Interstate_5_in_California" title="Interstate 5 in California">
       Interstate 5 in California
      </a>
      to allow travel from San Francisco to Los Angeles. These were to be followed by the Washington, D.C. to Boston corridor. Each swapping station costs
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$500,000
      </span>
      and stocks about 50 batteries. The service would be offered for the price of about 15 US gallons (57 l; 12 imp gal) of gasoline at the current local rate, around
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$60
      </span>
      to
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$80
      </span>
      at June 2013 prices. Owners can pick up their original battery pack fully charged on the return trip, which is included in the swap fee. Tesla would also offer the option to keep the swapped battery for a fee or to receive the original pack from Tesla for a fee. Pricing has not been determined.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Swapping01_214-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Swapping01-214">
        [208]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Tesla's only battery swap station is located at Harris Ranch, California, and was available for pilot testing in late December 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-216">
       <a href="#cite_note-216">
        [210]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , Tesla says they have hundreds of cars in the battery swap program, although few owners are interested in using the service.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-217">
       <a href="#cite_note-217">
        [211]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In June 2015, Tesla said that it was unlikely that more battery swap stations would be added due to lack of demand for battery swaps costing around $60 when supercharging is included free with most models.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-218">
       <a href="#cite_note-218">
        [212]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h2>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Editions">
       Editions
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: Editions">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h2>
     <p>
      Tesla allocated the first 1,000 units to its Signature and Signature Performance limited edition configurations, equipped with the 85 kWh battery pack, and priced in the U.S. at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$95,400
      </span>
      and
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$105,400
      </span>
      respectively, not including any applicable
      <a href="/wiki/Government_incentives_for_plug-in_electric_vehicles#United_States" title="Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles">
       U.S. federal and local government tax credits and incentives
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-GCR062112_219-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-GCR062112-219">
        [213]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NYT050611_220-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NYT050611-220">
        [214]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of July 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , the base Model S starts at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$75,000
      </span>
      with a 70 kWh battery pack and goes up to
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$105,000
      </span>
      for the performance model with the 85 kWh pack before any government subsidies.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-my.teslamotors.com_81-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-my.teslamotors.com-81">
        [81]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla does not make a
      <a href="/wiki/Convertible" title="Convertible">
       convertible
      </a>
      Model S.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-221">
       <a href="#cite_note-221">
        [215]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-222">
       <a href="#cite_note-222">
        [216]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      A custom Model S was designed for the
      <a href="/wiki/Oceanic_Preservation_Society" title="Oceanic Preservation Society">
       Oceanic Preservation Society
      </a>
      in collaboration with
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Obscura_Digital" title="Obscura Digital">
       Obscura Digital
      </a>
      , and was used to project images of endangered animals to help educate the public about the ongoing
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Holocene_mass_extinction" title="Holocene mass extinction">
       Holocene mass extinction
      </a>
      , as featured in the 2015 documentary
      <i>
       <a href="/wiki/Racing_Extinction" title="Racing Extinction">
        Racing Extinction
       </a>
      </i>
      .
     </p>
     <h2>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Sales_and_markets">
       Sales and markets
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: Sales and markets">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h2>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Global">
       Global
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Global">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_first_deliveries.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1328" data-file-width="2000" height="146" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Tesla_Model_S_first_deliveries.jpg/220px-Tesla_Model_S_first_deliveries.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Tesla_Model_S_first_deliveries.jpg/330px-Tesla_Model_S_first_deliveries.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Tesla_Model_S_first_deliveries.jpg/440px-Tesla_Model_S_first_deliveries.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_first_deliveries.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Model S first retail deliveries ceremony at the
        <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Factory" title="Tesla Factory">
         Tesla Factory
        </a>
        in
        <a href="/wiki/Fremont,_California" title="Fremont, California">
         Fremont, California
        </a>
        , held on June 22, 2012
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      Tesla Motors reported 520 reservations for the Model S during the first week they were available
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-223">
       <a href="#cite_note-223">
        [217]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and by December 2012, a total 15,000 net reservations (after deliveries and cancellations) had been received by year-end.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2012_224-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2012-224">
        [218]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The special edition Model S Signature model was sold out before deliveries began in June 2012, and according to Tesla Motors all models were sold out for that year shortly after. A car ordered in May 2012 would be delivered in early to mid-2013.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-225">
       <a href="#cite_note-225">
        [219]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-226">
       <a href="#cite_note-226">
        [220]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Initially Tesla expected to reach global sales of 35,000 units in 2014, but in November 2014 reduced its sales target to 33,000 units due to a deficit in production of 2,000 units during the third quarter of 2014. The company expected its annual production to increase by over 50% in 2014 to 35,000 units, and another increase of 50% in 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla3Q2014_227-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla3Q2014-227">
        [221]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla Motors set a target of between 50,000 and 52,000 deliveries for Model S and
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Model_X" title="Tesla Model X">
       Model X
      </a>
      cars in 2015, and delivered 50,658 units.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla092015_228-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla092015-228">
        [222]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2015_229-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2015-229">
        [223]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla plans to deliver 80,000 to 90,000 new Model S and Model X vehicles in 2016.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2015_229-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2015-229">
        [223]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dt>
       2012
      </dt>
     </dl>
     <p>
      U.S. deliveries began June 2012.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-MSlaunch_10-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-MSlaunch-10">
        [10]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Deliveries of the 60 kWh model were rescheduled from November 2012 to January/February 2013.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Deliver4060_230-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Deliver4060-230">
        [224]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A total of 2,650 cars were delivered in North America in 2012.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Sales2012_231-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Sales2012-231">
        [225]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dt>
       2013
      </dt>
     </dl>
     <p>
      During the first six months of 2013, 10,050 were delivered.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla1Q2013_232-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla1Q2013-232">
        [226]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Model S was released in Europe in early August 2013, and the first deliveries took place in Norway, Switzerland and the Netherlands,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-DeliveryEU_233-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-DeliveryEU-233">
        [227]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and by November 2013, the Model S was on sale in 20 countries.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-3Q2013Report_205-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-3Q2013Report-205">
        [199]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Sales totaled about 22,477 units in North America and Europe,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla2013Sales_234-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla2013Sales-234">
        [228]
       </a>
      </sup>
      surpassing Tesla's annual sales target of 21,500 units.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelS25K_235-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelS25K-235">
        [229]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Global cumulative sales passed the 25,000 unit milestone in December 2013.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelS25K_235-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelS25K-235">
        [229]
       </a>
      </sup>
      By the end of 2013, according to
      <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk" title="Elon Musk">
       Elon Musk
      </a>
      , Norway and Switzerland became the company's largest per capita sales markets.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-236">
       <a href="#cite_note-236">
        [230]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <table cellpadding="1" style="border-style:solid; border-width:1px; border-color:#c0c0c0; background-color:#fdfdfd; text-align:left; float: right; clear: right; margin: 0.5em 0 0.5em 1em;">
      <caption style="font-weight:bold">
       Tesla Model S global sales by quarter
      </caption>
      <tr>
       <th scope="col">
        Quarter
       </th>
       <th scope="col" style="width: 20em};">
        Units sold
       </th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
       <th scope="row" style="font-weight:normal;">
        3Q 2012
       </th>
       <td>
        <div style="height: 1.25em; width: 20em;">
         <div style="position: absolute; background-color: rgb(206, 223, 242); width:0.3em; height: 1.25em; margin: 0 0 0 0; z-index: 0;">
         </div>
         <span style="position: absolute; height:1.25em; width: 20em; padding: 0 0 0 2em; z-index: 10;">
          <span class="nowrap">
           250
          </span>
         </span>
        </div>
       </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
       <th scope="row" style="font-weight:normal;">
        4Q 2012
       </th>
       <td>
        <div style="height: 1.25em; width: 20em;">
         <div style="position: absolute; background-color: rgb(206, 223, 242); width:2.7em; height: 1.25em; margin: 0 0 0 0; z-index: 0;">

           2,400
          </span>
         </span>
        </div>
