     </table>
     <dl>
      <dt>
       2014
      </dt>
     </dl>
     <p>
      Retail deliveries in China began in April 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ChinaFirst_237-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ChinaFirst-237">
        [231]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The
      <a href="/wiki/Right-_and_left-hand_traffic" title="Right- and left-hand traffic">
       right-hand-drive model
      </a>
      was released in the UK in June 2014,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-UKfirst_238-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-UKfirst-238">
        [232]
       </a>
      </sup>
      followed by Hong Kong in July 2014,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1stHK_239-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-1stHK-239">
        [233]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and Japan in September 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-240">
       <a href="#cite_note-240">
        [234]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Deliveries in Australia began in December 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-241">
       <a href="#cite_note-241">
        [235]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Global cumulative sales of the Model S passed the 50,000 unit mark in October 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelS75K_242-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelS75K-242">
        [236]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A total of 31,655 units were sold worldwide in 2014, allowing the Model S to rank as the world's second best selling plug-in electric vehicle after the
      <a href="/wiki/Nissan_Leaf" title="Nissan Leaf">
       Nissan Leaf
      </a>
      that year.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Top102014_25-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Top102014-25">
        [25]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In 2014 about 55% of Model S deliveries took place in North America, 30% in Europe, and 15% in the Asia-Pacific market.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2014_243-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2014-243">
        [237]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dt>
       2015
      </dt>
     </dl>
     <p>
      A total of 21,577 units were sold worldwide during the first half of 2015, of which, 11,532 were delivered during the second quarter alone, up about 52% over the same quarter the previous year.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelS2Q2015_244-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelS2Q2015-244">
        [238]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelS062015_245-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelS062015-245">
        [239]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla1Q2015_246-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla1Q2015-246">
        [240]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of June 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , the Model S was sold in 30 countries.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelS2Q2015_244-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelS2Q2015-244">
        [238]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A total of 11,597 Model S cars were delivered during the third quarter, up about 49% over the same quarter in 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla092015_228-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla092015-228">
        [222]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A total of 17,272 Model S were delivered during the fourth quarter, up 76% over the same quarter the previous year, and setting a new record for the most cars delivered in a quarter.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2015_229-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2015-229">
        [223]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelS4Q2015_247-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelS4Q2015-247">
        [241]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Global Model S sales passed the 100,000 unit milestone in December 2015, three years and a half after its introduction.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelS100K_21-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelS100K-21">
        [21]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A total of 50,446 Model S sedans were sold globally in 2015, allowing the Model S to rank as the world's best-selling plug-in electric car in 2015, ahead of the Nissan Leaf (about 43,000 units).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Top2015Global_24-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-Top2015Global-24">
        [24]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2015_229-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2015-229">
        [223]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      As of December 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , a total of 107,228 Model S sedans have been sold worldwide since its introduction, ranking as the world's second best selling plug-in car ever after the Nissan Leaf (200,000).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Top2015Global_24-4">
       <a href="#cite_note-Top2015Global-24">
        [24]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2015_229-4">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2015-229">
        [223]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The United States is the leading market with 63,161 units sold.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2015_229-5">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2015-229">
        [223]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Sales2013US_248-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Sales2013US-248">
        [242]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Norway is the Model S largest overseas market,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-auto_249-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-auto-249">
        [243]
       </a>
      </sup>
      with 10,062 new units registered,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NorwaySales2013_250-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NorwaySales2013-250">
        [244]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-OFV2014_251-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-OFV2014-251">
        [245]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-OFV2015_252-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-OFV2015-252">
        [246]
       </a>
      </sup>
      followed by China with 5,524 units registered through September 2015,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-China092015_55-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-China092015-55">
        [55]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-China2014_253-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-China2014-253">
        [247]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and the Netherlands with 4,462 units registered at the end of December 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-RAISales2012_13_254-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-RAISales2012_13-254">
        [248]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-RAISales2014_255-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-RAISales2014-255">
        [249]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-RAISales2015_256-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-RAISales2015-256">
        [250]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Nether2012_15_257-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Nether2012_15-257">
        [251]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dt>
       2016
      </dt>
     </dl>
     <p>
      Model S global sales totaled 12,420 units during the first quarter of 2016.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1Q2016_258-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-1Q2016-258">
        [252]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Sales during the second quarter of 2016 were lower than anticipated by Tesla, with 9,764 Model S cars delivered worldwide during the quarter. Although production was up 20% from the previous quarter, the number of vehicles in transit at the end of June 2016 was much higher than expected (5,150 including
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Model_X" title="Tesla Model X">
       Model X
      </a>
      cars), representing 35.8% of the number of cars delivered in the quarter (14,402 vehicles including the Model X).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla2Q2016_259-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla2Q2016-259">
        [253]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla062016_260-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla062016-260">
        [254]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Deliveries in the third quarter of 2016 totaled 16,047 units, for cumulative sales of 38,231 Model S cars during the first nine months of 2016.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla3Q2016_22-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla3Q2016-22">
        [22]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1Q2016_258-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-1Q2016-258">
        [252]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla2Q2016_259-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla2Q2016-259">
        [253]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of September 2016
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , cumulative global sales totaled almost 145,500 units, with the U.S. ranking as the leading market.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla3Q2016_22-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla3Q2016-22">
        [22]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-VoltUS100K_23-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-VoltUS100K-23">
        [23]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>

       <td class="table-na" data-sort-value="" style="background: #ececec; color: #2C2C2C; vertical-align: middle; font-size: smaller; text-align: center;">
        N/A
       </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
       <td style="text-align:left;">
        <span class="flagicon">
         <img alt="" class="thumbborder" data-file-height="1000" data-file-width="1500" height="15" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/03/Flag_of_Italy.svg/23px-Flag_of_Italy.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/03/Flag_of_Italy.svg/35px-Flag_of_Italy.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/03/Flag_of_Italy.svg/45px-Flag_of_Italy.svg.png 2x" width="23"/>
        </span>

     </table>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Asia.2FPacific">
       Asia/Pacific
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=28" title="Edit section: Asia/Pacific">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:TeslaModelS_Signature_Japan_CHAdeMO2.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2864" data-file-width="4032" height="156" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/TeslaModelS_Signature_Japan_CHAdeMO2.jpg/220px-TeslaModelS_Signature_Japan_CHAdeMO2.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/TeslaModelS_Signature_Japan_CHAdeMO2.jpg/330px-TeslaModelS_Signature_Japan_CHAdeMO2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/TeslaModelS_Signature_Japan_CHAdeMO2.jpg/440px-TeslaModelS_Signature_Japan_CHAdeMO2.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:TeslaModelS_Signature_Japan_CHAdeMO2.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Model S at a quick charging
        <a href="/wiki/CHAdeMO" title="CHAdeMO">
         CHAdeMO
        </a>
        station in Japan.
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      <b>
       Australia
      </b>
     </p>
     <p>
      The first nine units were delivered in Sydney on December 9, 2014. Tesla Motors also opened its first store and service centre in
      <a href="/wiki/St_Leonards,_New_South_Wales" title="St Leonards, New South Wales">
       St Leonards
      </a>
      , and its first Supercharger station at
      <a href="/wiki/Pyrmont,_New_South_Wales" title="Pyrmont, New South Wales">
       Pyrmont
      </a>
      in December 2014. Initially, only two versions were available, the 60 starting at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       A$91,400
      </span>
      , and the 85 starting at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       A$103,400
      </span>
      before any options, stamp duty and the Australian luxury car tax (LCT). The Model S P85D, starting at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       A$133,500
      </span>
      , had deliveries scheduled to begin in June 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-293">
       <a href="#cite_note-293">
        [281]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-294">
       <a href="#cite_note-294">
        [282]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      As of December 2014
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , a total of 65 Model S cars were registered in
      <a href="/wiki/New_South_Wales" title="New South Wales">
       New South Wales
      </a>
      and only four in
      <a href="/wiki/Victoria_(Australia)" title="Victoria (Australia)">
       Victoria
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Australia2014_1Q2015_295-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Australia2014_1Q2015-295">
        [283]
       </a>
      </sup>
      At the end of March 2015, registrations totaled 119 in New South Wales and 54 in Victoria. Although there were no sales figures reported for Tesla in other states, the combined sales of these two states alone were enough for the Model S to rank as the top selling all-electric car in the country for the first quarter of 2015, ahead of the BMW i3 (46) and the Nissan Leaf (31).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Australia2014_1Q2015_295-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Australia2014_1Q2015-295">
        [283]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dt>
       China
      </dt>
     </dl>
     <p>
      The first deliveries took place on April 22, 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ChinaFirst_237-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-ChinaFirst-237">
        [231]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Model S has the same standard equipment as the continental European version, but was adapted to provide larger back seats because the car was expected to be driven by a
      <a href="/wiki/Chauffeur" title="Chauffeur">
       chauffeur
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla3Q2013_296-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla3Q2013-296">
        [284]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Only two versions with an 85 kWh battery pack are available in the Chinese market, standard and performance.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-PriceChina_297-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-PriceChina-297">
        [285]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Pricing starts at CN¥734,000 (~
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$121,200
      </span>
      ),
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-PriceChina_297-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-PriceChina-297">
        [285]
       </a>
      </sup>
      similar to the US, adding only taxes and transportation costs. Comparable luxury cars cost more than
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$180,000
      </span>
      in the Chinese market.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-298">
       <a href="#cite_note-298">
        [286]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-299">
       <a href="#cite_note-299">
        [287]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Chinese sales up to June 2014 were estimated between 1,000 to 1,300 units.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-China2Q2014_01_300-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-China2Q2014_01-300">
        [288]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-China2Q2014_02_301-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-China2Q2014_02-301">
        [289]
       </a>
      </sup>
      JLWarren Capital, an equity firm, estimated that about 2,800 Tesla Model S cars have been imported to China by mid September 2014, but only 432 had received the license plates.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ChinaModelS_302-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ChinaModelS-302">
        [290]
       </a>
      </sup>
      According to a Tesla spokesman, the major reasons for the discrepancy could be that registration rules were holding deliveries in Shanghai, and Tesla only recently was able to start delivering the electric cars to customers who bought them in Shanghai. Secondly, many Chinese customers have delayed taking possession of their Model S car while waiting for the government to add the Tesla to the list of electric vehicles exempt from its 8% to 10% purchase tax.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ChinaModelS_302-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-ChinaModelS-302">
        [290]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-303">
       <a href="#cite_note-303">
        [291]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of December 2014
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , Tesla had imported 4,800 Model S cars, but only 2,499 of those vehicles were registered for road use in China.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-China2014_253-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-China2014-253">
        [247]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Tesla's CEO expressed disappointment with the Chinese sales, as stock continued to be high by early 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-304">
       <a href="#cite_note-304">
        [292]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As sales improved, Model S sales reached 2,147 units representing an 80% share of the imported plug-in hybrid or electric car segment in China for the first half of 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-China062015_305-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-China062015-305">
        [293]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Sales totaled 3,025 units during the first nine months of 2015,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-China092015_55-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-China092015-55">
        [55]
       </a>
      </sup>
      for cumulative registrations of 5,524 units through September 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-China092015_55-4">
       <a href="#cite_note-China092015-55">
        [55]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-China2014_253-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-China2014-253">
        [247]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dt>
       Hong Kong
      </dt>
     </dl>
     <p>
      Sales of the Model S began in July 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1stHK_239-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-1stHK-239">
        [233]
       </a>
      </sup>
      After the introduction of the Model S, sales of all-electric cars took off in Hong Kong.
      <sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">
       [
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">
         <span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (July 2016)">
          citation needed
         </span>
        </a>
       </i>
       ]
      </sup>
      Thanks to tax waiver on electric vehicles, the Model S price is very competitive in the luxury car segment. While the after tax price of the Model S 70D is HK$619,000, a
      <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_E-Class_(W212)" title="Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W212)">
       Mercedes-Benz E 200 Premium Edition
      </a>
      costs HK$1,009,500.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-QuatzHK_306-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-QuatzHK-306">
        [294]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of June 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , an EV enthusiasts group estimated that the Model S was the top selling all-electric car in the territory with roughly 70% of the registered stock of EVs.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-QuatzHK_306-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-QuatzHK-306">
        [294]
       </a>
      </sup>
      According to Tesla, as of June 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , Hong Kong has the world's highest density of
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Motors#Supercharger_network" title="Tesla Motors">
       Tesla superchargers
      </a>
      , with eight stations comprising a total of 36 supercharger stalls. This infrastructure allows most Model S owners to have a supercharger within 20 minutes' drive.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-307">
       <a href="#cite_note-307">
        [295]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Sales totaled 2,221 units in 2015,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-HK2015_277-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-HK2015-277">
        [267]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and by August 2016 about 80% of 5,800 EVs in Hong Kong were Teslas.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-308">
       <a href="#cite_note-308">
        [296]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Europe">
       Europe
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=29" title="Edit section: Europe">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_delivery_to_H%C3%B8yres_Nikolai_Astrup_in_Norway.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="3456" data-file-width="5184" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Tesla_Model_S_delivery_to_H%C3%B8yres_Nikolai_Astrup_in_Norway.jpg/220px-Tesla_Model_S_delivery_to_H%C3%B8yres_Nikolai_Astrup_in_Norway.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Tesla_Model_S_delivery_to_H%C3%B8yres_Nikolai_Astrup_in_Norway.jpg/330px-Tesla_Model_S_delivery_to_H%C3%B8yres_Nikolai_Astrup_in_Norway.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Tesla_Model_S_delivery_to_H%C3%B8yres_Nikolai_Astrup_in_Norway.jpg/440px-Tesla_Model_S_delivery_to_H%C3%B8yres_Nikolai_Astrup_in_Norway.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Tesla_Model_S_delivery_to_H%C3%B8yres_Nikolai_Astrup_in_Norway.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        The first European deliveries took place at Tesla's store in
        <a href="/wiki/Oslo" title="Oslo">
         Oslo
        </a>
        in August 2013.
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      Retail deliveries began in Europe in early August 2013, in Norway, Switzerland and the Netherlands.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-DeliveryEU_233-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-DeliveryEU-233">
        [227]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The two biggest markets for the Model S in Europe are Norway and the Netherlands.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TopMarkets_309-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-TopMarkets-309">
        [297]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Model S, with about 3,900 units sold, ended 2013 as the third-best selling all-electric car in Europe after the Nissan Leaf and the
      <a href="/wiki/Renault_Zoe" title="Renault Zoe">
       Renault Zoe
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EU2013_310-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-EU2013-310">
        [298]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EU122013_311-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-EU122013-311">
        [299]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A total of 8,734 Model S cars were sold in 2014, representing a market share of 15.5% of new all-electric passenger car sales in Europe,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Leaf2014EU_312-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Leaf2014EU-312">
        [300]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and again allowing the Model S to rank as the third best selling all-electric car in Europe after the Leaf and the Zoe.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Leaf2014EU_312-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Leaf2014EU-312">
        [300]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Accounting for sales during the first nine months of 2014, the Model S outsold the
      <a href="/wiki/Audi_A8" title="Audi A8">
       Audi A8
      </a>
      ,
      <a href="/wiki/BMW_7_Series" title="BMW 7 Series">
       BMW 7 Series
      </a>
      and
      <a href="/wiki/Jaguar_XJ" title="Jaguar XJ">
       Jaguar XJ
      </a>
      , ranking second in the European
      <a href="/wiki/Luxury_vehicle" title="Luxury vehicle">
       luxury vehicle
      </a>
      segment after the
      <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_S-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz S-Class">
       Mercedes-Benz S-Class
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-313">
       <a href="#cite_note-313">
        [301]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      European Model S sales in 2015 totaled 15,515 units, ranking second after the Renault Zoe (18,727) and ahead of the Leaf (15,455). The Model S captured 15.9% of the European all-electric segment sales in 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-BEV2015EU_314-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-BEV2015EU-314">
        [302]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Model S topped the European luxury car segment in 2015, ahead of the Mercedes-Benz S-Class (14,990), the segment's leader in previous years.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-315">
       <a href="#cite_note-315">
        [303]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Norway was the leading market in 2015 with 4,039 units sold.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-OFV2015_252-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-OFV2015-252">
        [246]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Cumulative Model S sales in Europe totaled 28,149 units by the end of 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EU2013_310-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-EU2013-310">
        [298]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Leaf2014EU_312-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-Leaf2014EU-312">
        [300]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-BEV2015EU_314-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-BEV2015EU-314">
        [302]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      <b>
       Pricing
      </b>
     </p>
     <p>
      American and European standard equipment and options packages are the same. European prices are higher, due to
      <a href="/wiki/Exchange_rate" title="Exchange rate">
       exchange rates
      </a>
      , the
      <a href="/wiki/Value-added_tax" title="Value-added tax">
       value-added tax
      </a>
      (VAT), plus transport costs, import duties and other country-specific costs. In most countries where the Model S is sold base prices for the 60 kWh start at €72,600, and €83,150 for the 85 kWh battery car. The 85 kWh Performance, Signature, and Signature Performance trim levels are listed at €97,550, €101,400, and €110,950 respectively. Tesla offered a deduction of €1,700 to buyers who held a reservation by the end of December 2012.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-316">
       <a href="#cite_note-316">
        [304]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-317">
       <a href="#cite_note-317">
        [305]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      <b>
       Sales by country
      </b>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dd>
       <b>
        Czech Republic
       </b>
      </dd>
     </dl>
     <p>
      A total of 23 units were sold during 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-318">
       <a href="#cite_note-318">
        [306]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dd>
       <b>
        Denmark
       </b>
      </dd>
     </dl>
     <p>
      During its first full month in the Danish market, the Model S was the top selling electric vehicle with 42 units sold.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-319">
       <a href="#cite_note-319">
        [307]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Sales were 112 units in 2013 and 460 in 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Denmark2013_16_268-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Denmark2013_16-268">
        [259]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Model S sales constituted 35% of the sales of luxury cars by mid 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-320">
       <a href="#cite_note-320">
        [308]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A Model S was tested as a taxi, but high price and low range made the project uneconomic.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-321">
       <a href="#cite_note-321">
        [309]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-pol2014-08_322-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-pol2014-08-322">
        [310]
       </a>
      </sup>
      When the AWD model was announced in Autumn 2014, used Model S were sold fast at high price.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-pol2014-10_323-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-pol2014-10-323">
        [311]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In October 2015, the
      <a href="/wiki/Folketing" title="Folketing">
       Danish Parliament
      </a>
      approved to phase out the tax exemption for electric vehicles, and customers rushed to order the Model S before the price increase. It became the most sold car of any kind in Denmark in December 2015, with 1,248 cars delivered that month, out of 1,573 electric cars sold in December. This is the first time ever that an electric car is the best selling car in Denmark.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Denmark2015_20-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Denmark2015-20">
        [20]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Model S comprised 98% of
      <a href="/wiki/F-segment" title="F-segment">
       luxury cars
      </a>
      sold in Denmark in 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-324">
       <a href="#cite_note-324">
        [312]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Cumulative sales in the country reached 3,308 units through December 2015, of which, a record of 2,736 units were sold in 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Denmark2013_16_268-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-Denmark2013_16-268">
        [259]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Sales plummeted to 49 cars in the first half year after the tax increase.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-325">
       <a href="#cite_note-325">
        [313]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dd>
       <b>
        Germany
       </b>
      </dd>
     </dl>
     <p>
      Model S customers in Germany are offered a free optional high speed tuning for
      <a href="/wiki/Autobahn" title="Autobahn">
       Autobahn
      </a>
      driving. The company announced that by November 2013 the first Tesla stations would open between Munich and Stuttgart, Munich and Zurich, Switzerland, and Cologne and Frankfurt. Tesla Motors planned to cover more than 50% of Germany by the end of March 2014, and 100% by the end of 2014. Germany would then have the most Superchargers per capita of any country. German stations would support 135
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/KW" title="KW">
       kW
      </a>
      charging.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-326">
       <a href="#cite_note-326">
        [314]
       </a>
      </sup>
      By late 2013 Tesla announced a goal to sell 10,000 Model S in Germany in 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-327">
       <a href="#cite_note-327">
        [315]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      A total of 183 units were registered in the country during 2013.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Ger2013Sales_269-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Ger2013Sales-269">
        [260]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Registrations totaled 815 units in 2014, representing 2.7% of the luxury segment sales in the country.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SalesGer2014_270-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-SalesGer2014-270">
        [261]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of November 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , cumulative registrations totaled 2,354 units.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Ger2013Sales_269-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-Ger2013Sales-269">
        [260]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SalesGer2014_270-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-SalesGer2014-270">
        [261]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SalesGer112015_328-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-SalesGer112015-328">
        [316]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dd>
       <b>
        Netherlands
       </b>
      </dd>
     </dl>
     <p>
      The first deliveries in the country occurred on August 22, 2013, at Tesla's European Distribution Center in
      <a href="/wiki/Tilburg" title="Tilburg">
       Tilburg
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tilburg_51-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tilburg-51">
        [51]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A total of 1,194 units were sold in 2013.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-RAISales2012_13_254-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-RAISales2012_13-254">
        [248]
       </a>
      </sup>
      After the end of the
      <a href="/wiki/Plug-in_electric_vehicles_in_the_Netherlands#Government_incentives" title="Plug-in electric vehicles in the Netherlands">
       registration tax exemption
      </a>
      , sales fell significantly, and only 262 units were sold during the first four months of 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-RAISales042014_329-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-RAISales042014-329">
        [317]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Sales in 2015 totaled 1,805 units.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-RAISales2015_256-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-RAISales2015-256">
        [250]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Model S leads the Dutch all-electric segment with 4,382 cars registered at the end of December 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Nether2012_15_257-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Nether2012_15-257">
        [251]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dd>
       <b>
        Norway
       </b>
      </dd>
     </dl>
     <p>
      The first delivery of a Model S in Europe took place in
      <a href="/wiki/Oslo" title="Oslo">
       Oslo
      </a>
      on August 7, 2013.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-330">
       <a href="#cite_note-330">
        [318]
       </a>
      </sup>
      By the end of August 2013, Europe's first six charging stations were opened, in
      <a href="/wiki/Lyngdal" title="Lyngdal">
       Lyngdal
      </a>
      ,
      <a href="/wiki/Aurland" title="Aurland">
       Aurland
      </a>
      ,
      <a href="/wiki/Domb%C3%A5s" title="Dombås">
       Dombås
      </a>
      ,
      <a href="/wiki/Gol,_Norway" title="Gol, Norway">
       Gol
      </a>
      ,
      <a href="/wiki/Sundebru" title="Sundebru">
       Sundebru
      </a>
      and
      <a href="/wiki/Lillehammer" title="Lillehammer">
       Lillehammer
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SuperchargerNor_204-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-SuperchargerNor-204">
        [198]
       </a>
      </sup>
      That month 186 units were delivered, ranking second among all-electric cars behind the Nissan Leaf (448 units).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NorwaySales082013_331-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NorwaySales082013-331">
        [319]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Sales surged in September totaling 616 units, beating the Leaf and achieving an overall new car market share of 5.1%.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SalesNorway092013_16-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-SalesNorway092013-16">
        [16]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NorwayTop1_17-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-NorwayTop1-17">
        [17]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NorwayTop2_18-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-NorwayTop2-18">
        [18]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <div class="thumb tleft">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Five_Tesla_Model_S_electric_cars_in_Norway.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2000" data-file-width="3000" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Five_Tesla_Model_S_electric_cars_in_Norway.jpg/220px-Five_Tesla_Model_S_electric_cars_in_Norway.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Five_Tesla_Model_S_electric_cars_in_Norway.jpg/330px-Five_Tesla_Model_S_electric_cars_in_Norway.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Five_Tesla_Model_S_electric_cars_in_Norway.jpg/440px-Five_Tesla_Model_S_electric_cars_in_Norway.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Five_Tesla_Model_S_electric_cars_in_Norway.jpg" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        As of December 2015
        <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
         <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
          [update]
         </a>
        </sup>
        , Norway is the second largest Model S market by volume, with about 9.4% of cumulative global sales.
        <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Top2015Global_24-7">
         <a href="#cite_note-Top2015Global-24">
          [24]
         </a>
        </sup>
        Shown in
        <a href="/wiki/Geiranger" title="Geiranger">
         Geiranger
        </a>
        .
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      In 2013, a five-month waiting list emerged creating a used market, with
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$10,000
      </span>
      to
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$20,000
      </span>
      premiums for a used model.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-332">
       <a href="#cite_note-332">
        [320]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-333">
       <a href="#cite_note-333">
        [321]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Sales dropped to 98 units in October,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SalesNorway102013_334-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-SalesNorway102013-334">
        [322]
       </a>
      </sup>
      before jumping back to 527 units in November, ranking it number two in new car registrations after the
      <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Golf" title="Volkswagen Golf">
       Volkswagen Golf
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SalesNorway112013_335-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-SalesNorway112013-335">
        [323]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In December, sales of 553 units made it the top-selling new car again and capturing a 4.9% market share of new car sales.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NorwayTop3_19-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-NorwayTop3-19">
        [19]
       </a>
      </sup>
      With less than five months of sales, the Model S ranked 20th for the year with a market share of 1.4% of Norwegian new car sales, Tesla's largest in Europe.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TopNorway2013_336-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-TopNorway2013-336">
        [324]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-337">
       <a href="#cite_note-337">
        [325]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The Model S topped the monthly sales ranking for a third time in March 2014, with 1,493 units sold, breaking the 28-year-old monthly sales record, surpassing the
      <a href="/wiki/Ford_Sierra" title="Ford Sierra">
       Ford Sierra
      </a>
      , which sold 1,454 units in May 1986.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Norway1Q2014_338-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Norway1Q2014-338">
        [326]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-339">
       <a href="#cite_note-339">
        [327]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Sales totaled 2,056 Model S cars during the first quarter of 2014, making the Model S the best selling new car in Norway during this period. The Model S captured a 5.6% market share of new car sales and 38.8% of the new plug-in electric car segment during this quarter.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Norway1Q2014_338-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Norway1Q2014-338">
        [326]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NorwayEVSales032014_340-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NorwayEVSales032014-340">
        [328]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-341">
       <a href="#cite_note-341">
        [329]
       </a>
      </sup>
      By the end of 2014, the Model S ranked as the fifth best selling new car in the Norwegian market, with 4,040 units registered and a market share of 2.8% of new car sales in the country that year.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-OFV2014_251-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-OFV2014-251">
        [245]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      As of July 2014
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , Norway ranked as Tesla's largest overseas market, with an average of 436 Model S sedans sold per month since August 2013. In comparison, the average in the United States was about 1,630 units delivered per month since the electric car went on sales in 2012.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-auto_249-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-auto-249">
        [243]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of December 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , Norway continued as the second largest Model S market by volume, with about 9.4% of cumulative global sales.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Top2015Global_24-8">
       <a href="#cite_note-Top2015Global-24">
        [24]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Since its introduction, a total of 10,871 Model S new cars have sold in Norway through April 2016.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NorwaySales2013_250-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-NorwaySales2013-250">
        [244]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-OFV2014_251-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-OFV2014-251">
        [245]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-OFV2015_252-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-OFV2015-252">
        [246]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-OFV042016_342-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-OFV042016-342">
        [330]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dd>
       <b>
        Switzerland
       </b>
      </dd>
     </dl>
     <p>
      Retail deliveries began in August 2013,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-DeliveryEU_233-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-DeliveryEU-233">
        [227]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and a total of 213 units were registered in 2013.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SalesSwiss2013_16_276-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-SalesSwiss2013_16-276">
        [266]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Model S, with 496 units registered, ranked as the top selling plug-in electric car in the country in 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-343">
       <a href="#cite_note-343">
        [331]
       </a>
      </sup>
      With 835 units sold during the first seven months of 2015, the Model S outsold combined Swiss sales of the
      <a href="/wiki/Luxury_vehicle" title="Luxury vehicle">
       luxury
      </a>
      segment including such models as the
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Mercedes_S-Class" title="Mercedes S-Class">
       Mercedes S-Class
      </a>
      ,
      <a href="/wiki/Audi_A8" title="Audi A8">
       Audi A8
      </a>
      and
      <a href="/wiki/BMW_7_Series" title="BMW 7 Series">
       BMW 7 Series
      </a>
      during the same period.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-344">
       <a href="#cite_note-344">
        [332]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Cumulative Model S sales totaled 3,060 units up until June 2016, which includes units sold in
      <a href="/wiki/Liechtenstein" title="Liechtenstein">
       Liechtenstein
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SalesSwiss2013_16_276-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-SalesSwiss2013_16-276">
        [266]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <dl>
      <dd>
       <b>
        United Kingdom
       </b>
      </dd>
     </dl>
     <p>
      Deliveries began in June 2014,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-UKfirst_238-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-UKfirst-238">
        [232]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and a total of 698 units were registered in the UK by the end of 2014.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-UKcum1Q2015_345-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-UKcum1Q2015-345">
        [333]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Pricing starts at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       GB£54,380
      </span>
      before the
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       GB£5,000
      </span>
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Plug-in_Car_Grant" title="Plug-in Car Grant">
       Plug-in Car Grant
      </a>
      . Model S owners are also exempted from the
      <a href="/wiki/London_congestion_charge" title="London congestion charge">
       London congestion charge
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-346">
       <a href="#cite_note-346">
        [334]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A total of 3,312 Model S sedans were registered in the UK at the end of June 2016.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-UK2Q2016_274-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-UK2Q2016-274">
        [265]
       </a>
      </sup>
      During the first half of 2016, slightly more Model S cars were registered in the UK than in Norway, the leading Model S market in Europe. During the first six months of 2016 a total of 1,263 Model S sedans were registered in the UK and 1,248 in Norway.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-347">
       <a href="#cite_note-347">
        [335]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="North_America_2">
       North America
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=30" title="Edit section: North America">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      <b>
       Canada
      </b>
     </p>
     <p>
      The first Model S sedans were delivered in December 2012. Cumulative sales totaled 3,590 units as of December 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , and ranks as the second best-selling plug-in car in the country ever after the Chevrolet Volt (5,415) and ahead of the Nissan Leaf (3,198). The Model S was the top selling plug-in electric car in Canada in 2015 with 2,010 units sold.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SalesCanada2012_16_267-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-SalesCanada2012_16-267">
        [258]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      <b>
       Mexico
      </b>
     </p>
     <p>
      Retail sales began in
      <a href="/wiki/Mexico_City" title="Mexico City">
       Mexico City
      </a>
      in December 2015. Initially, no Supercharger stations are available in the country.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-348">
       <a href="#cite_note-348">
        [336]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      <b>
       United States
      </b>
     </p>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Model_S,_as_imagined_by_the_WSJ.png">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="937" data-file-width="1537" height="134" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Model_S%2C_as_imagined_by_the_WSJ.png/220px-Model_S%2C_as_imagined_by_the_WSJ.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Model_S%2C_as_imagined_by_the_WSJ.png/330px-Model_S%2C_as_imagined_by_the_WSJ.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Model_S%2C_as_imagined_by_the_WSJ.png/440px-Model_S%2C_as_imagined_by_the_WSJ.png 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Model_S,_as_imagined_by_the_WSJ.png" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        Personalized delivery of a Tesla Model S in the U.S.
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      The first delivery took place on June 1, 2012.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-349">
       <a href="#cite_note-349">
        [337]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Deliveries for retail customers in the United States started on June 22, at a special event held at the
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Factory" title="Tesla Factory">
       Tesla Factory
      </a>
      in
      <a href="/wiki/Fremont,_California" title="Fremont, California">
       Fremont, California
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-MSlaunch_10-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-MSlaunch-10">
        [10]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The first 1,000 production units were Signature and Signature Performance limited editions equipped with an 85 kWh battery pack.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2012_224-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2012-224">
        [218]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Cumulative sales passed the 50,000 unit milestone in early July 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CumSales062015US_350-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-CumSales062015US-350">
        [338]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      About 2,620 units were sold in the U.S. during 2012 out of 2,650 units delivered in North America.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2012_224-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2012-224">
        [218]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Sales2013US_248-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-Sales2013US-248">
        [242]
       </a>
      </sup>
      California is the largest American regional market for the Model S.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TopMarkets_309-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-TopMarkets-309">
        [297]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In March 2013, Tesla reported the delivery of the 3,000th Model S in California, representing around 50% of US sales to that date.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-351">
       <a href="#cite_note-351">
        [339]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-352">
       <a href="#cite_note-352">
        [340]
       </a>
      </sup>
      During the first quarter of 2013 the Model S ranked as the top selling
      <a href="/wiki/Plug-in_electric_vehicle" title="Plug-in electric vehicle">
       plug-in electric vehicle
      </a>
      in the U.S. with about 4,900 units delivered, followed by the
      <a href="/wiki/Chevrolet_Volt" title="Chevrolet Volt">
       Chevrolet Volt
      </a>
      with 4,244 units.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla1Q2013_232-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla1Q2013-232">
        [226]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-PEVSales032013US_353-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-PEVSales032013US-353">
        [341]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-354">
       <a href="#cite_note-354">
        [342]
       </a>
      </sup>
      During 2013, the Model S was listed as the least stolen car in the United States, with a theft rating of just 0.15 per 1,000 units produced. By comparison, the U.S. average is 3.51 cars stolen per 1,000 produced. The
      <a href="/wiki/Honda_Accord" title="Honda Accord">
       Honda Accord
      </a>
      was the most stolen car in the U.S. in 2013, with about 54,000 units, mostly models built in 2007 or before.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-355">
       <a href="#cite_note-355">
        [343]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <div class="thumb tleft">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Model_S_04_2015_SFO_2457.JPG">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1200" data-file-width="1800" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ea/Model_S_04_2015_SFO_2457.JPG/220px-Model_S_04_2015_SFO_2457.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ea/Model_S_04_2015_SFO_2457.JPG/330px-Model_S_04_2015_SFO_2457.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ea/Model_S_04_2015_SFO_2457.JPG/440px-Model_S_04_2015_SFO_2457.JPG 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">
         <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Model_S_04_2015_SFO_2457.JPG" title="Enlarge">
         </a>
        </div>
        California is the top selling regional market of the Model S. Shown in San Francisco.
        <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Calif_356-0">
         <a href="#cite_note-Calif-356">
          [344]
         </a>
        </sup>
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
     <p>
      According to
      <a href="/wiki/Edmunds.com" title="Edmunds.com">
       Edmunds.com
      </a>
      , between January and August 2013 the Model S achieved a high
      <a href="/wiki/Market_share" title="Market share">
       market share
      </a>
      of new car sales among the U.S. most expensive
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ZIP_code" title="ZIP code">
       ZIP codes
      </a>
      , as rated by
      <a href="/wiki/Forbes" title="Forbes">
       Forbes
      </a>
      , led by California.
      <a href="/wiki/Atherton,_California" title="Atherton, California">
       Atherton
      </a>
      ranked first with a 15.4% share, followed by
      <a href="/wiki/Los_Altos_Hills,_California" title="Los Altos Hills, California">
       Los Altos Hills
      </a>
      with 11.9%, and
      <a href="/wiki/Portola_Valley,_California" title="Portola Valley, California">
       Portola Valley
      </a>
      with 11.2%. During this period the Model S had the highest number of new passenger car registrations in 8 of the 25 most expensive American ZIP codes.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-357">
       <a href="#cite_note-357">
        [345]
       </a>
      </sup>
      With 8,347 units sold in 2013, it was the third-best selling luxury car in California (after the
      <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_E-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz E-Class">
       Mercedes-Benz E-Class
      </a>
      and
      <a href="/wiki/BMW_5_Series" title="BMW 5 Series">
       BMW 5 Series
      </a>
      sedans),
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-358">
       <a href="#cite_note-358">
        [346]
       </a>
      </sup>
      with a 9.8% share of the Californian luxury and sports segment.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-359">
       <a href="#cite_note-359">
        [347]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of November 2013
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , the Model S was available nationwide with California leading sales with a 48% share of national sales.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Calif_356-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Calif-356">
        [344]
       </a>
      </sup>
      During the first nine months of 2015, with 7,736 units registered, the Model S captured a 11.4% market share of the luxury and sports segment in California and ranked third after the Mercedes-Benz E-Class (8,583) and BMW 5 Series (8,207).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Calif3Q2015_360-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Calif3Q2015-360">
        [348]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Model S was the top selling car in the luxury and sports segment in the first quarter of 2016, with a market share of 13.5% of the segment registrations in California.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-361">
       <a href="#cite_note-361">
        [349]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Calif1Q2016_362-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Calif1Q2016-362">
        [350]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      American sales totaled about 18,650 units in 2013,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-USModelS18K_199-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-USModelS18K-199">
        [193]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Sales2014US_363-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Sales2014US-363">
        [351]
       </a>
      </sup>
      placing the Model S as the third selling plug-in electric car after the
      <a href="/wiki/Chevrolet_Volt" title="Chevrolet Volt">
       Chevrolet Volt
      </a>
      (23,094) and the Nissan Leaf (22,610).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Sales2013US_248-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-Sales2013US-248">
        [242]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Also in 2013, the Model S was the top seller in the
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Full-size_luxury_car" title="Full-size luxury car">
       full-size luxury
      </a>
      <a href="/wiki/Sedan_(automobile)" title="Sedan (automobile)">
       sedan
      </a>
      category, ahead of the
      <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_S-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz S-Class">
       Mercedes-Benz S-Class
      </a>
      at 13,303.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-USModelS18K_199-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-USModelS18K-199">
        [193]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In 2014, 16,689 Model S sedans were delivered, down 10.5% from 2013, but the electric sedan ranked again as the third best selling plug-in car in the U.S.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2015_229-9">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2015-229">
        [223]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Sales2014US_363-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Sales2014US-363">
        [351]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In 2015 the Model S ranked as the top selling plug-in electric car in the U.S, with 25,202 units sold surpassed both the Leaf (17,296) and the Volt (15,393).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Sales2015US_26-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Sales2015US-26">
        [26]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelSTop2015US_27-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelSTop2015US-27">
        [27]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2015_229-10">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2015-229">
        [223]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Model S was also the country's best-selling car in the large luxury segment among comparably priced four-door sedans, ahead of the
      <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_S-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz S-Class">
       Mercedes-Benz S-Class
      </a>
      (21,934) and
      <a href="/wiki/BMW_7_Series" title="BMW 7 Series">
       BMW 7 Series
      </a>
      (9,292).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2015_229-11">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2015-229">
        [223]
       </a>
      </sup>
      By the end of 2015, cumulative sales in the American market represented almost 60% of global sales since the introduction of the Model S.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Top2015Global_24-9">
       <a href="#cite_note-Top2015Global-24">
        [24]
       </a>
      </sup>
      An estimated 74,861 Model S cars have been sold in the United States through June 2016.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Tesla4Q2015_229-12">
       <a href="#cite_note-Tesla4Q2015-229">
        [223]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Sales2013US_248-4">
       <a href="#cite_note-Sales2013US-248">
        [242]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Sales062016US_262-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-Sales062016US-262">
        [255]
       </a>
      </sup>
      According to Tesla, with 9,156 units sold in third quarter of 2016, up 59% from the same quarter in 2015, the Model S led sales in the large luxury car segments, representing almost a third of the segment sales, and ahead of the Mercedes-Benz S-Class (4,921) and the BMW 7 Series (3,634).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-364">
       <a href="#cite_note-364">
        [352]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Model S continued to rank as the top selling plug-in electric in the American market during the first three quarters of 2016 with about 21,000 units sold.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Sales092016US_365-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Sales092016US-365">
        [353]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      <b>
       Owners
      </b>
     </p>
     <p>
      Owners of the Model S are overwhelmingly male and over 45 years old.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-366">
       <a href="#cite_note-366">
        [354]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      <b>
       Retail sales model
      </b>
     </p>
     <div class="hatnote" role="note">
      Main article:
      <a href="/wiki/Tesla_US_dealership_disputes" title="Tesla US dealership disputes">
       Tesla sales model
      </a>
     </div>
     <p>
      Tesla Motors sells its cars directly to consumers without creating a dealer network, as other manufacturers have done and as many states require by legislation. In support of its approach, the company has fought legal and legislative battles in Ohio, New Jersey, New York and other states.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-367">
       <a href="#cite_note-367">
        [355]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-368">
       <a href="#cite_note-368">
        [356]
       </a>
      </sup>
      With law changes in recent years in New Jersey, New York, Maryland, Ohio, and Pennsylvania the Tesla direct sales model is permitted in 22 states as of March 2015.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-369">
       <a href="#cite_note-369">
        [357]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-370">
       <a href="#cite_note-370">
        [358]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of May 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      the sales procedure in other states such as Texas is somewhat different with the Tesla salesperson being prevented from discussing prices, the actual sale having to be made online and the sales tax having to be paid up front. Delivery of a Tesla car to a Texas address is no different than in other states.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-371">
       <a href="#cite_note-371">
        [359]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Consequently, while Tesla showcases and sells its cars directly to the consumer in
      <i>
       Tesla Stores
      </i>
      abroad, it operates a mix of
      <i>
       Tesla Stores
      </i>
      and
      <i>
       Tesla Galleries
      </i>
      in the US.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-372">
       <a href="#cite_note-372">
        [360]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      <b>
       Pricing
      </b>
     </p>
     <p>
      In June 2012, the Model S Signature model was priced at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$95,400
      </span>
      and the Signature Performance model at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$105,400
      </span>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-GCR062112_219-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-GCR062112-219">
        [213]
       </a>
      </sup>
      On November 29, 2012, Tesla announced an all model price increase of
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$2,500
      </span>
      for new reservations, starting January 1, 2013. The price of a pre-paid 60 kWh replacement pack was
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$10,000
      </span>
      , while the 85 kWh pack was priced at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$12,000
      </span>
      , in 2013.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2013Price_373-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-2013Price-373">
        [361]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As of June 2014
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , the model with the 60 kWh pack begins at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$69,900
      </span>
      , the base model with the 85 kWh pack starts at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$79,900
      </span>
      , and the P85 performance model at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$93,400
      </span>
      . As of April 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , the Model S begins at
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$75,000
      </span>
      for the 70 kWh dual-motor edition,
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$80,000
      </span>
      for the 85 kWh single motor edition,
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$85,000
      </span>
      for the 85 kWh dual-motor edition, and
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$105,000
      </span>
      for the 85 kWh dual-motor performance edition. These prices do not reflect
      <a href="/wiki/Government_incentives_for_plug-in_electric_vehicles#United_States" title="Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles">
       U.S. federal and local government tax credits or purchase incentives
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TMOptions_102-3">
       <a href="#cite_note-TMOptions-102">
        [102]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      As of 2016
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , with the exception of used Teslas, all plug-in models
      <a href="/wiki/Depreciation" title="Depreciation">
       depreciate
      </a>
      more rapidly than conventionally powered cars and trucks, according to
      <a href="/wiki/NerdWallet" title="NerdWallet">
       NerdWallet
      </a>
      . For all-electric cars depreciation varies between 60% to 75% in three years. In contrast, most conventionally powered vehicles in the same period depreciate between 45% to 50%. However, the Tesla Model S is more like conventional cars, with three-year depreciation of about 40%.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CSM092016_374-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-CSM092016-374">
        [362]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      According to Black Book, a three-year-old Model S sells for about 62% of its original price.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-375">
       <a href="#cite_note-375">
        [363]
       </a>
      </sup>
      According to Autolist, a
      <a href="/wiki/Used_car" title="Used car">
       used
      </a>
      Model S with 50,000 mi (80,000 km) on the odometer loses 28% value on average; less than similar cars.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-376">
       <a href="#cite_note-376">
        [364]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h2>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Safety">
       Safety
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=31" title="Edit section: Safety">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h2>
     <div class="thumb tright">
      <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
       <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:2013_Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B,_rear_right.jpg">
        <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2728" data-file-width="5284" height="114" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/2013_Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B%2C_rear_right.jpg/220px-2013_Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B%2C_rear_right.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/2013_Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B%2C_rear_right.jpg/330px-2013_Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B%2C_rear_right.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/2013_Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B%2C_rear_right.jpg/440px-2013_Tesla_Model_S_P85%2B%2C_rear_right.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
       </a>
       <div class="thumbcaption">
        <div class="magnify">

        Tesla Model S P85+ (US)
       </div>

     </div>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Safety_features">
       Safety features
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=32" title="Edit section: Safety features">

     <p>
      The Model S is one of just a few cars to have ever achieved a 5-star safety rating from both Euro NCAP and the U.S. National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-377">
       <a href="#cite_note-377">
        [365]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-378">
       <a href="#cite_note-378">
        [366]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Only two other cars have earned the same recognition since 2011 (when the NHTSA introduced its latest rating scheme).
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-379">
       <a href="#cite_note-379">
        [367]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">
       [
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Identifying_reliable_sources" title="Wikipedia:Identifying reliable sources">
         <span title="The material near this tag may rely on an unreliable source. (August 2016)">
          unreliable source?
         </span>
        </a>
       </i>
       ]
      </sup>
     </p>

         <img alt="" data-file-height="110" data-file-width="108" height="11" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/11px-Star_full.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/17px-Star_full.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/22px-Star_full.svg.png 2x" width="11"/>
        </span>
       </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
       <td>
        <a href="/wiki/Rollover" title="Rollover">
         Rollover
        </a>
       </td>
       <td>
        <span style="white-space:nowrap" title="5/5 stars">
         <img alt="5/5 stars" data-file-height="110" data-file-width="108" height="11" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/11px-Star_full.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/17px-Star_full.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/22px-Star_full.svg.png 2x" title="5/5 stars" width="11"/>
         <img alt="" data-file-height="110" data-file-width="108" height="11" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/11px-Star_full.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/17px-Star_full.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/22px-Star_full.svg.png 2x" width="11"/>
         <img alt="" data-file-height="110" data-file-width="108" height="11" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/11px-Star_full.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/17px-Star_full.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/22px-Star_full.svg.png 2x" width="11"/>
         <img alt="" data-file-height="110" data-file-width="108" height="11" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/11px-Star_full.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/17px-Star_full.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/22px-Star_full.svg.png 2x" width="11"/>
         <img alt="" data-file-height="110" data-file-width="108" height="11" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/11px-Star_full.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/17px-Star_full.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Star_full.svg/22px-Star_full.svg.png 2x" width="11"/>
        </span>

        <small>
         5.7%
        </small>
       </td>
