     </table>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="First_crash_with_battery_fire">
       First crash with battery fire
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=33" title="Edit section: First crash with battery fire">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <div class="hatnote" role="note">
      See also:
      <a href="/wiki/Plug-in_electric_vehicle_fire_incidents#Tesla_Model_S" title="Plug-in electric vehicle fire incidents">
       Tesla Model S fire incidents
      </a>
     </div>
     <p>
      The first widely reported Model S fire occurred several minutes after the vehicle hit metal debris on the
      <a href="/wiki/Washington_State_Route_167" title="Washington State Route 167">
       Washington State Route 167
      </a>
      highway in
      <a href="/wiki/Kent,_Washington" title="Kent, Washington">
       Kent, Washington
      </a>
      on October 1, 2013.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelSfire01_382-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelSfire01-382">
        [370]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The driver "was able to exit the highway as instructed by the onboard alert system, bring the car to a stop and depart the vehicle without injury".
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelSfire03_383-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelSfire03-383">
        [371]
       </a>
      </sup>
      He then contacted authorities and, while awaiting their arrival, smoke began coming out the front of the vehicle. The driver stated that he hit something while exiting the
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/HOV_lane" title="HOV lane">
       HOV lane
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelSfire01_382-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelSfire01-382">
        [370]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-384">
       <a href="#cite_note-384">
        [372]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-385">
       <a href="#cite_note-385">
        [373]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla stated that the fire was caused by the "direct impact of a large metallic object to one of the 16
      <a href="/wiki/Battery_(electricity)" title="Battery (electricity)">
       battery
      </a>
      modules", and that by design, the modules were separated by firewalls, limiting the fire to "a small section in the front of the vehicle".
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelSfire01_382-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelSfire01-382">
        [370]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      The module was evidently punctured by a "curved section" that fell off a truck and was recovered near the accident. Tesla stated that the debris punched a 3-inch (76 mm) diameter hole through the .25-inch (6.4 mm) armor plate under the vehicle, applying force of some 25
      <a href="/wiki/Ton" title="Ton">
       tons
      </a>
      . Built-in vents directed the flames away from the vehicle so that the fire did not enter the passenger compartment. According to Tesla, the firefighters followed standard procedure; using large amounts of water to extinguish the fire was correct,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Model_S_First_Responder_Guide_386-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-Model_S_First_Responder_Guide-386">
        [374]
       </a>
      </sup>
      however, puncturing the metal firewall to gain access to the fire also allowed the flames to spread to the front trunk.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelSfire03_383-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelSfire03-383">
        [371]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla also stated that because the battery pack contains "only about 10% of the energy contained in a gasoline tank", the effective combustion potential of a single module is only about 1% that of a conventional vehicle.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ModelSfire03_383-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-ModelSfire03-383">
        [371]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      On October 24, 2013, the U.S.
      <a href="/wiki/National_Highway_Traffic_Safety_Administration" title="National Highway Traffic Safety Administration">
       National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
      </a>
      (NHTSA) announced, "After reviewing all available data, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration has not found evidence at this time that would indicate the recent battery fire involving a Tesla Model S was the result of a vehicle safety defect or noncompliance with federal safety standards."
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-387">
       <a href="#cite_note-387">
        [375]
       </a>
      </sup>
      But the following month, the NHTSA opened a preliminary evaluation to determine "the potential risks associated with undercarriage strikes on model year 2013 Tesla Model S vehicles".
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NYT11192013_388-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NYT11192013-388">
        [376]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-389">
       <a href="#cite_note-389">
        [377]
       </a>
      </sup>
      On March 28, 2014, NHTSA closed its investigation, claiming that the new titanium underbody shield and aluminum deflector plates, along with increased ground clearance, "should reduce both the frequency of underbody strikes and the resultant fire risk".
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-390">
       <a href="#cite_note-390">
        [378]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Subsequent_fires">
       Subsequent fires
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=34" title="Edit section: Subsequent fires">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      On November 6, 2013 another fire broke out after a Model S struck a
      <a href="/wiki/Tow_hitch" title="Tow hitch">
       tow hitch
      </a>
      on the roadway, causing damage beneath the vehicle.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NYT112013_391-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NYT112013-391">
        [379]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The incidents led Tesla to extend its vehicle warranty to cover fire damage and to apply a software update to increase ground clearance when operating at highway speed.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NYT11192013_388-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-NYT11192013-388">
        [376]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-392">
       <a href="#cite_note-392">
        [380]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Another fire incident took place in Toronto, Canada, in early February 2014. The Model S was parked in a garage and was not charging when the fire started. The origin of the fire is undetermined.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-393">
       <a href="#cite_note-393">
        [381]
       </a>
      </sup>
      According to Tesla "in this particular case, we don't yet know the precise cause, but have definitively determined that it did not originate in the battery, the charging system, the adapter or the electrical receptacle, as these components were untouched by the fire".
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-394">
       <a href="#cite_note-394">
        [382]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Starting with vehicle bodies manufactured as of 6 March 2014
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , all units were outfitted with a triple underbody shield. Existing cars were retrofitted upon request or as part of a normally scheduled service.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-395">
       <a href="#cite_note-395">
        [383]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-396">
       <a href="#cite_note-396">
        [384]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      On 1 January 2016, a 2014 Model S caught fire in Norway while supercharging unsupervised. The vehicle was totally destroyed but nobody was injured.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-397">
       <a href="#cite_note-397">
        [385]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-398">
       <a href="#cite_note-398">
        [386]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-399">
       <a href="#cite_note-399">
        [387]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The fire was slow, and the owner had time to unplug the car and retrieve possessions.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-vg18March2016_400-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-vg18March2016-400">
        [388]
       </a>
      </sup>
      An investigation by the
      <a href="/wiki/Accident_Investigation_Board_Norway" title="Accident Investigation Board Norway">
       Norwegian Accident Investigation Board (AIBN)
      </a>
      indicated that the fire originated in the car, but was otherwise inconclusive.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-401">
       <a href="#cite_note-401">
        [389]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In March 2016, Tesla stated that their own investigation into the incident concluded that the fire was caused by a short circuit in the vehicle's distribution box, but that the amount of damage prevented them from determining the exact cause.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-vg18March2016_400-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-vg18March2016-400">
        [388]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla stated that the Supercharger detected the short circuit and deactivated, and a future Model S software update would stop the vehicle from charging if a short circuit is detected.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-402">
       <a href="#cite_note-402">
        [390]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Recalls">
       Recalls
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=35" title="Edit section: Recalls">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      On November 20, 2015, Tesla announced a voluntary worldwide recall of all of its 90,000 Model S vehicles, in order to check for a possible defect in the cars' front seat belt assemblies. The problem was raised in early November by one customer in Europe. Tesla's resulting investigation was unable to identify a root cause for the failure, and the company decided to examine every single car. Tesla reported that there have been no accidents or injuries related to the problem.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-403">
       <a href="#cite_note-403">
        [391]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-404">
       <a href="#cite_note-404">
        [392]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h2>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Recognition">
       Recognition
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=36" title="Edit section: Recognition">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h2>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Awards">
       Awards
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=37" title="Edit section: Awards">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <ul>
      <li>
       2013 AutoGuide.com Reader's Choice Car of the Year
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-405">
        <a href="#cite_note-405">
         [393]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </li>
      <li>
       2013
       <a href="/wiki/World_Car_of_the_Year" title="World Car of the Year">
        World Green Car of the Year
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-406">
        <a href="#cite_note-406">
         [394]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </li>
      <li>
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Automobile_Magazine" title="Automobile Magazine">
        Automobile Magazine
       </a>
       's 2013 Car of the Year, a unanimous decision.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2013_Automobile_of_the_Year:_Tesla_Model_S_407-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-2013_Automobile_of_the_Year:_Tesla_Model_S-407">
         [395]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </li>
      <li>
       <a href="/wiki/CNET" title="CNET">
        CNET
       </a>
       Tech Car of the Year for 2012
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-408">
        <a href="#cite_note-408">
         [396]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </li>
      <li>
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Consumer_Reports" title="Consumer Reports">
         Consumer Reports
        </a>
       </i>
       gave the Model S a score of 103 out of 100, its highest ever. The Model S broke the rating scale of Consumer Reports during its most recent test.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-409">
        <a href="#cite_note-409">
         [397]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </li>
      <li>
       <i>
        Consumer Reports'
       </i>
       2013 survey of owner satisfaction produced a score of 99 out of 100, "the highest the magazine has seen in years."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-410">
        <a href="#cite_note-410">
         [398]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In 2014 the Model S topped for the second year in a row
       <i>
        Consumer Reports
       </i>
       survey of owner satisfaction. This time the Model S had a score of 98 out of 100.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-411">
        <a href="#cite_note-411">
         [399]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </li>
      <li>
       <i>
        Consumer Reports
       </i>
       found the Model S to be 'Best Overall' for 2014 across all 10 categories of cars, light trucks and SUVs, chosen from more than 260 vehicles the organization has recently tested. The magazine considers the Model S a "technological tour de force, while pricey, is brimming with innovation."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-412">
        <a href="#cite_note-412">
         [400]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In 2015 they rated the Model S at 103 (breaking the scale).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-413">
        <a href="#cite_note-413">
         [401]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-414">
        <a href="#cite_note-414">
         [402]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </li>
      <li>
       Green Car Reports' Best Car To Buy 2013
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-415">
        <a href="#cite_note-415">
         [403]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </li>
      <li>
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Motor_Trend" title="Motor Trend">
         Motor Trend
        </a>
       </i>
       2013
       <a href="/wiki/Motor_Trend_Car_of_the_Year" title="Motor Trend Car of the Year">
        Car of the Year
       </a>
       , also a unanimous decision and the first winner in the award's history to not be powered by an internal combustion engine.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2013_Motor_Trend_Car_of_the_Year:_Tesla_Model_S_416-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-2013_Motor_Trend_Car_of_the_Year:_Tesla_Model_S-416">
         [404]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </li>
      <li>
       <a href="/wiki/Natural_Resources_Canada" title="Natural Resources Canada">

       </a>

       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-417">
        <a href="#cite_note-417">
         [405]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </li>
      <li>
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Popular_Science" title="Popular Science">

        </a>
        '
       </i>
       s Auto Grand Award Winner Best of What's New list 2012.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-418">
        <a href="#cite_note-418">
         [406]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </li>
      <li>
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Daily_Telegraph" title="The Daily Telegraph">
         The Telegraph
        </a>
       </i>
       included the Model S in its list of the top 10 cars that changed the world published in December 2014, and also named the electric sedan the most important car of the last 20 years.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-419">

     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Distance_records">
       Distance records
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=38" title="Edit section: Distance records">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      As of August 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , the distance record is 452.8 mi (728.7 km) in a Model S on a single charge. It was made by Norwegian Bjørn Nyland and his friend, Morgan Tørvolt on a flat stretch with low traffic around the supercharger in
      <a href="/wiki/R%C3%B8dekro" title="Rødekro">
       Rødekro
      </a>
      , Denmark. They used
      <a href="/wiki/Energy-efficient_driving" title="Energy-efficient driving">
       hypermiling
      </a>
      techniques such as front motor only, low speed (39 km/h) and no airconditioning.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NylandDist_425-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-NylandDist-425">
        [413]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-426">
       <a href="#cite_note-426">
        [414]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The previous record was 425.8 miles (685.3 km), made overnight on February 14, 2013 by Bruno Bowden.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-427">
       <a href="#cite_note-427">
        [415]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-428">
       <a href="#cite_note-428">
        [416]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-429">
       <a href="#cite_note-429">
        [417]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The first record of 423.5 miles (681.6 km) was set during November 2012 by David and Adam Metcalf.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-430">
       <a href="#cite_note-430">
        [418]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-431">
       <a href="#cite_note-431">
        [419]
       </a>
      </sup>
      These attempts were inspired by a blog written by Elon Musk about the planned range and efficiency of the Tesla Model S, offering a prize for anyone exceeding 400 miles (640 km) on a single charge, where it was estimated the 85 kwh model could do it by driving at a constant 36 mph (58 km/h) under ideal conditions.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-432">
       <a href="#cite_note-432">
        [420]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h2>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Controversies">
       Controversies
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=39" title="Edit section: Controversies">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h2>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Range_limitation">
       Range limitation
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=40" title="Edit section: Range limitation">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      On February 8, 2013,
      <i>
       <a href="/wiki/The_New_York_Times" title="The New York Times">
        The New York Times
       </a>
      </i>
      published a review by John M. Broder about a trip between Washington, D.C., and Boston using Tesla's Supercharger network. At the time it included only two stations on the
      <a href="/wiki/East_Coast_of_the_United_States" title="East Coast of the United States">
       East Coast
      </a>
      . Broder made a variety of critical claims about the battery's performance in cold weather and the distance between charging stations. The trip ended with the Model S carried by a
      <a href="/wiki/Flatbed_truck" title="Flatbed truck">
       flatbed truck
      </a>
      to the
      <a href="/wiki/Milford,_Connecticut" title="Milford, Connecticut">
       Milford, Connecticut
      </a>
      , station.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-433">
       <a href="#cite_note-433">
        [421]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Tesla responded by publishing logs of the vehicle's charge levels and driving speed that contradicted Broder's account on several factual details.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-434">
       <a href="#cite_note-434">
        [422]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla implied that Broder's behavior forced the car to fail. Broder replied to the criticism in a blog post and suggested that the speed discrepancies may have been because the car had been equipped with
      <a href="/wiki/Wheel_sizing#Wheel_size" title="Wheel sizing">
       19-inch wheels rather than the specified 21-inch wheels
      </a>
      .
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-435">
       <a href="#cite_note-435">
        [423]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In the midst of the controversy, a
      <a href="/wiki/CNN" title="CNN">
       CNN
      </a>
      reporter recreated Broder's trip without exhausting the battery. However, two key differences distinguished the two journeys. The weather was about 10 °F (6 °C) warmer and CNN did the trip in one day; the
      <i>
       Times
      </i>
      let the car sit overnight without being plugged in.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-436">
       <a href="#cite_note-436">
        [424]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A reporter from
      <a href="/wiki/CNBC" title="CNBC">
       CNBC
      </a>
      also recreated the trip in one day without incidents.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-437">
       <a href="#cite_note-437">
        [425]
       </a>
      </sup>
      One week later, a group of Tesla owners recreated Broder's trip without problems. One owner was delayed because his car failed to charge and required two
      <a href="/wiki/Firmware" title="Firmware">
       firmware
      </a>
      updates.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-438">
       <a href="#cite_note-438">
        [426]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-439">
       <a href="#cite_note-439">
        [427]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      On February 18, 2013,
      <i>
       New York Times
      </i>
      <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Public_Editor" title="Public Editor">
       Public Editor
      </a>
      Margaret Sullivan published an editorial stating that Broder took "casual and imprecise notes" of his test drive and did not use good judgment, but she maintained that the article was done in good faith. She also claimed that Broder's vehicle logs were "sometimes quite misleading."
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-440">
       <a href="#cite_note-440">
        [428]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-441">
       <a href="#cite_note-441">
        [429]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-442">
       <a href="#cite_note-442">
        [430]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In July and September 2014 tests performed by an independent German car magazine in cooperation with the TÜV (German Association for Technical Inspection) and Tesla owners seemed to reveal issues with the battery's performance. According to the magazine, Tesla did not take up the invitation to repeat the test, and also seemed to refuse to offer vehicles for a second test.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-443">
       <a href="#cite_note-443">
        [431]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-444">
       <a href="#cite_note-444">
        [432]
       </a>
      </sup>
      A test performed by another German publication ("
      <a href="/wiki/Die_Welt" title="Die Welt">
       Die Welt
      </a>
      ") supported the findings.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-445">
       <a href="#cite_note-445">
        [433]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="NHTSA_safest_car">
       NHTSA safest car
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=41" title="Edit section: NHTSA safest car">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      On August 19, 2013, based on NHTSA safety ratings, a Tesla press release claimed that the Model S had achieved the best safety rating of any car ever tested. Tesla stated, "NHTSA does not publish a star rating above 5, however safety levels better than 5 stars
      <i>
       are
      </i>
      captured in the overall Vehicle Safety Score (VSS) provided to manufacturers, where the Model S achieved a new combined record of 5.4 stars."
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-446">
       <a href="#cite_note-446">
        [434]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-447">
       <a href="#cite_note-447">
        [435]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-448">
       <a href="#cite_note-448">
        [436]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-449">
       <a href="#cite_note-449">
        [437]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-450">
       <a href="#cite_note-450">
        [438]
       </a>
      </sup>
      However, a few days later NHTSA rebutted Tesla's claim, explaining that the rating for the Model S was equal to any other car receiving 5-stars, and claiming that the carmaker did not follow its advertising guidelines.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-451">
       <a href="#cite_note-451">
        [439]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-452">
       <a href="#cite_note-452">
        [440]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-453">
       <a href="#cite_note-453">
        [441]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Power_dissipation_when_not_in_use">
       Power dissipation when not in use
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=42" title="Edit section: Power dissipation when not in use">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      Older versions of the system software suffered from power drain issues when the car wasn't being used, with the batteries losing 4.5 kWh overnight (known commonly as "vampire drain").
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-454">
       <a href="#cite_note-454">
        [442]
       </a>
      </sup>
      System software v5.8 (v1.49.30), released December 12, 2013, reduced overnight energy loss substantially, to 1.1 kWh per night, or around 3 miles.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-vampire_90-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-vampire-90">
        [90]
       </a>
      </sup>
      In January 2014, Bjørn Nyland, a Model S owner in Norway, recorded a range loss of approximately 20% during a 27-day extended vacation, an indicated range loss of 63 miles (101 km), or 2.3 miles (3.7 km) per day, while stored in frigid temperatures without any charging cable attached.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-455">
       <a href="#cite_note-455">
        [443]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Consumer_Reports.27_recommendation">
       Consumer Reports' recommendation
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=43" title="Edit section: Consumer Reports' recommendation">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      In October 2015, two months after naming the Tesla 'the best car ever tested,' Consumer Reports declined to give the Tesla Model S a "recommended" designation, citing too many complaints from owners. Complaints ranged from minor, such as misaligned doors and squeaky body, to severe - things like total drive train replacement and inoperable door handles. Tesla's shares dropped 15%, both because of the magazine's cut and because of concerns over the Tesla Model X luxury SUV.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CR2015_29-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-CR2015-29">
        [29]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-456">
       <a href="#cite_note-456">
        [444]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Similarly, Edmunds.com found quality and safety issues in their long-term road test and "amassed quite the repair résumé during the last 17 months."
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-457">
       <a href="#cite_note-457">
        [445]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Both Edmunds and Consumer Reports reported issues, including the vehicle stalling while driving.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-458">
       <a href="#cite_note-458">
        [446]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      In their 2016 Annual Auto Reliability Survey, Consumer Reports improved the Model S rating to average reliability, while reporting that the Model X has had significant malfunction issues. The magazine also raised "serious concerns about how some automakers, including Tesla, have designed, deployed, and marketed semi-autonomous technology."
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CR2016_30-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-CR2016-30">
        [30]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Power_discrepancy">
       Power discrepancy
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=44" title="Edit section: Power discrepancy">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      The P85D "Insane" was widely reported to have 691 horsepower,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-mtLudi_459-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-mtLudi-459">
        [447]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-S2015-03-11_460-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-S2015-03-11-460">
        [448]
       </a>
      </sup>
      but some owners reported 20% less power on
      <a href="/wiki/Dynamometer" title="Dynamometer">
       dynamometer
      </a>
      in various circumstances.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-dtDP_461-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-dtDP-461">
        [449]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-hcDP_462-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-hcDP-462">
        [450]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Manufacturers are required by EU law to display power "at full setting of the power controller" (from an external DC source when performing laboratory vehicle approval), but not necessarily to show power limited by battery. Other equipment must be removed, or their power added to the measurement.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-straubDP_463-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-straubDP-463">
        [451]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-464">
       <a href="#cite_note-464">
        [452]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Actual power available depends on circumstances,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-straubDP_463-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-straubDP-463">
        [451]
       </a>
      </sup>
      as it does for piston cars
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-465">
       <a href="#cite_note-465">
        [453]
       </a>
      </sup>
      which until 1972 could be 25–30% less than given.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-466">
       <a href="#cite_note-466">
        [454]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-467">
       <a href="#cite_note-467">
        [455]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      As of November 2015
      <sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
       <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit">
        [update]
       </a>
      </sup>
      , Tesla website shows battery-limited combined 463 hp for P85D (532 hp for "Ludicrous").
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-S2015-11-02_468-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-S2015-11-02-468">
        [456]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-dtDP_461-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-dtDP-461">
        [449]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Autonomy_limitations">
       Autonomy limitations
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=45" title="Edit section: Autonomy limitations">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      The autonomy features of the Model S, including Autosteer and
      <a href="/wiki/Autonomous_cruise_control_system" title="Autonomous cruise control system">
       Traffic-Aware Cruise Control
      </a>
      , have limitations that have led to collisions when the driver becomes inattentive.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-469">
       <a href="#cite_note-469">
        [457]
       </a>
      </sup>
      Tesla warns in the owners manual that drivers always must be aware of road conditions and not rely on the cruise control to prevent a collision,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-470">
       <a href="#cite_note-470">
        [458]
       </a>
      </sup>
      as the system may not detect stationary vehicles or obstacles, bicycles, and pedestrians. However, critics such as scientist
      <a href="/wiki/Andrew_Ng" title="Andrew Ng">
       Andrew Ng
      </a>
      have accused Tesla of being irresponsible by releasing a product with such limitations as it can lull drivers into a false sense of security.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-471">
       <a href="#cite_note-471">
        [459]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h3>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="Electrical_consumption_of_Tesla_Model_S">
       Electrical consumption of Tesla Model S
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=46" title="Edit section: Electrical consumption of Tesla Model S">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h3>
     <p>
      In early March 2016, a report by
      <a href="/wiki/Stuff_(magazine)" title="Stuff (magazine)">
       Stuff magazine
      </a>
      revealed that test performed by VICOM, Ltd on behalf of Singapore's Land Transport Authority had found a 2014 Tesla Model S to be consuming 444 Wh/km (0.715 kW·h/mi),
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-472">
       <a href="#cite_note-472">
        [460]
       </a>
      </sup>
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-473">
       <a href="#cite_note-473">
        [461]
       </a>
      </sup>
      which was greater than the 236 Wh/km (0.38 kW·h/mi) reported by the U.S Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-474">
       <a href="#cite_note-474">
        [462]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and the 181 Wh/km (0.291 kW·h/mi) reported by Tesla.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cleaninsingapore_475-0">
       <a href="#cite_note-cleaninsingapore-475">
        [463]
       </a>
      </sup>
      As a result, a carbon surcharge of S$15,000 (
      <span style="white-space: nowrap">
       US$10,900
      </span>
      ) was imposed on the Model S, making Singapore the only country in the world to impose an environmental surcharge on a fully electric car.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-476">
       <a href="#cite_note-476">
        [464]
       </a>
      </sup>
      The Land Transport Authority justified this by stating that it had to "account for CO
      <sub>
       2
      </sub>
      emissions during the electricity generation process" and therefore "a grid emission factor of 0.5g/watt-hour was also applied to the electric energy consumption",
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-477">
       <a href="#cite_note-477">
        [465]
       </a>
      </sup>
      however Tesla Motors countered that when the energy used to extract, refine, and distribute gasoline was taken into account, the Model S produces approximately one-third the CO
      <sub>
       2
      </sub>
      of an equivalent gasoline-powered vehicle.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cleaninsingapore_475-1">
       <a href="#cite_note-cleaninsingapore-475">
        [463]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <p>
      Later that month, the Land Transport Authority released a statement stating that they and the VICOM Emission Test Laboratory will be working with Tesla engineers to determine if there was a flaw in the test,
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-478">
       <a href="#cite_note-478">
        [466]
       </a>
      </sup>
      and a Tesla statement indicated that the discussions were "positive" and that they were confident of a quick resolution.
      <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cleaninsingapore_475-2">
       <a href="#cite_note-cleaninsingapore-475">
        [463]
       </a>
      </sup>
     </p>
     <h2>

     <h2>
      <span class="mw-headline" id="References">
       References
      </span>
      <span class="mw-editsection">
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        [
       </span>
       <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tesla_Model_S&amp;action=edit&amp;section=48" title="Edit section: References">
        edit
       </a>
       <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
        ]
       </span>
      </span>
     </h2>
     <div class="reflist columns references-column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;">
      <ol class="references">
       <li id="cite_note-Brian_Lam-1">
        <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
         ^
         <a href="#cite_ref-Brian_Lam_1-0">
          <sup>
           <i>
            <b>
             a
            </b>
           </i>
          </sup>
         </a>
         <a href="#cite_ref-Brian_Lam_1-1">
          <sup>
           <i>
            <b>
             b
            </b>
           </i>
          </sup>
         </a>
        </span>
        <span class="reference-text">
         <cite class="citation web">
          Lam, Brian (2007-02-19).
          <a class="external text" href="http://gizmodo.com/237952/tesla-whitestar-electric-sedan-4-doors-half-the-price-of-the-roadster" rel="nofollow">
           "Tesla Whitestar Electric Sedan: 4 Doors, Half the Price of the Roadster"
          </a>

         <span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATesla+Model+S&amp;rft.au=Jeff+Cobb&amp;rft.btitle=2014%27s+Top-10+Global+Best-Selling+Plug-in+Cars&amp;rft.date=2015-02-11&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.hybridcars.com%2F2014s-top-10-global-best-selling-plug-in-cars%2F10%2F&amp;rft.pub=HybridCars.com&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook">
          <span style="display:none;">

         <i>
          A total of 31,655 units were sold worldwide in 2014. Global cumulative sales since June 2012 totaled 56,782 Model S cars by the end of 2014.

         <span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATesla+Model+S&amp;rft.atitle=CORRECTED-%28OFFICIAL%29-UPDATE+2-Tesla+CEO+says+negotiating+with+China+on+local+production&amp;rft.au=Jake+Spring&amp;rft.date=2015-10-23&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.reuters.com%2Farticle%2F2015%2F10%2F24%2Ftesla-china-idUSL3N12N2RF20151024&amp;rft.jtitle=Reuters&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal">
          <span style="display:none;">
          </span>
         </span>
         <i>
          Tesla sold sold 3,025 Model S cars in China from January to September 2015.
         </i>
        </span>

           "Suspension"
          </a>

          <q>
           The Lotus Elise has a kinematic roll center height of 30mm above the ground and a center of gravity height of 470mm. The Lotus Elise RCH is 6% the height of the CG, meaning 6% of lateral force is transferred through the suspension arms and 94% is transferred through the springs and dampers.
          </q>

        <span class="reference-text">

          <q>
           This is the first known fatality in just over 130 million miles where Autopilot was activated. Among all vehicles in the US, there is a fatality every 94 million miles. Worldwide, there is a fatality approximately every 60 million miles.

          <span style="display:none;">
          </span>
         </span>
         <i>
          The Tesla Model S ranked as the third best selling all-electric passenger car and as the seventh among highway-capable plug-in electric vehicles.
         </i>
         .
        </span>
       </li>

         <span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATesla+Model+S&amp;rft.au=Association+Nationale+pour+le+D%C3%A9veloppement+de+la+Mobilit%C3%A9+Electrique+-+AVERE+France&amp;rft.btitle=Quelle+est+la+place+de+la+France+sur+le+march%C3%A9+europ%C3%A9en+du+v%C3%A9hicule+%C3%A9lectrique+%3F&amp;rft.date=2016-03-24&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.avere-france.org%2FSite%2FArticle%2F%3Farticle_id%3D6515%26from_espace_adherent%3D0&amp;rft.pub=AVERE&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook">
          <span style="display:none;">

         <i>
          A total of 97,687 all-electric vehicles were registered in the European market in 2015. The top selling electric cars were the Renault Zoe (18,727), the Tesla Model S (15,515), and the Nissan Leaf (15,455).
         </i>
        </span>

           ^

          <a class="external text" href="http://ofvas.no/bilsalget/bilsalget_2014/bilsalget_i_mars/" rel="nofollow">

         <span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATesla+Model+S&amp;rft.au=Norwegian+Road+Federation+%28OFV%29&amp;rft.btitle=Bilsalget+i+mars&amp;rft.date=2014-04&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fofvas.no%2Fbilsalget%2Fbilsalget_2014%2Fbilsalget_i_mars%2F&amp;rft.pub=OFV&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook">
          <span style="display:none;">
          </span>
         </span>
         <i>
          A total of 36,492 new passenger cars were registered in Norway during the first quarter of 2014. The Model S ranks first with 2,056 units and a market share of 5.6%, followed by the VW Golf with 1,577 (4.3%) and the Nissan Leaf with 1,559 (4.3%)
         </i>
        </span>

          <a class="external text" href="http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1087393_first-tesla-model-s-fire-caused-by-collision-with-road-debris" rel="nofollow">

          </a>
          . Green Car Reports
          <span class="reference-accessdate">
           . Retrieved
           <span class="nowrap">
            2014-10-23

         </cite>
         <span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATesla+Model+S&amp;rft.aufirst=John&amp;rft.aulast=Voelcker&amp;rft.btitle=First+Tesla+Model+S+Fire+Caused+By+Collision+With+Road+Debris&amp;rft.date=2013-10-03&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.greencarreports.com%2Fnews%2F1087393_first-tesla-model-s-fire-caused-by-collision-with-road-debris&amp;rft.pub=Green+Car+Reports&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook">
          <span style="display:none;">
          </span>

       <li id="cite_note-Model_S_First_Responder_Guide-386">
        <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
         <b>
          <a href="#cite_ref-Model_S_First_Responder_Guide_386-0">
           ^
          </a>
         </b>
        </span>
        <span class="reference-text">
         <cite class="citation book">
          <a class="external text" href="http://www.teslamotors.com/sites/default/files/downloads/en_EU/emergency_response_guide.pdf#page=20" rel="nofollow">
           <i>
            2012–2013 Model S Emergency Response Guide
           </i>
          </a>
          <span style="font-size:85%;">
           (PDF)
          </span>
          . Tesla Motors. 2013. p. 18
          <span class="reference-accessdate">
           . Retrieved
           <span class="nowrap">
            2014-10-23
           </span>
          </span>
          .
          <q>
           If the high voltage battery becomes involved in fire or is bent, twisted, damaged, or breached in any way, or if you suspect that the battery is heating, use large amounts of water to cool the battery. DO NOT extinguish fire with a small amount of water. Always establish or request an additional water supply.
          </q>
         </cite>
